'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Resolves CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
This adds support for legacy `callback`s and newer `callback_ex`s in `BIO_read`, `BIO_write`, and `BIO_free`. These callbacks provide the same API as OpenSSL 1.1.1 and 3.0.0 with the same semantics.

### Callouts
I'm not sure if reusing the logic in `call_bio_callback_with_processed` is helping or hurting the readability. I'm interested in feedback if it people prefer keeping that logic in `BIO_read` and `BIO_write`.

### Testing:
I created a simple mock callback to test this. I am looking for any better examples to make sure I implemented the behavior as expected. Right now the unit test is tightly coupled to the implementation and what my understanding of OpenSSL's code is doing. [bio.h](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/include/openssl/bio.h.in), [bio_lib.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/crypto/bio/bio_lib.c), and [docs](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man3.0/man3/BIO_set_callback_ex.html) for reference.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Resolves CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
This adds support for legacy `callback`s and newer `callback_ex`s in `BIO_read`, `BIO_write`, and `BIO_free`. These callbacks provide the same API as OpenSSL 1.1.1 and 3.0.0 with the same semantics.

### Callouts
I'm not sure if reusing the logic in `call_bio_callback_with_processed` is helping or hurting the readability. I'm interested in feedback if it people prefer keeping that logic in `BIO_read` and `BIO_write`.

### Testing:
I created a simple mock callback to test this. I am looking for any better examples to make sure I implemented the behavior as expected. Right now the unit test is tightly coupled to the implementation and what my understanding of OpenSSL's code is doing. [bio.h](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/include/openssl/bio.h.in), [bio_lib.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/crypto/bio/bio_lib.c), and [docs](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man3.0/man3/BIO_set_callback_ex.html) for reference.

Resolves CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
This adds support for legacy `callback`s and newer `callback_ex`s in `BIO_read`, `BIO_write`, and `BIO_free`. These callbacks provide the same API as OpenSSL 1.1.1 and 3.0.0 with the same semantics.

### Callouts
I'm not sure if reusing the logic in `call_bio_callback_with_processed` is helping or hurting the readability. I'm interested in feedback if it people prefer keeping that logic in `BIO_read` and `BIO_write`.

### Testing:
I created a simple mock callback to test this. I am looking for any better examples to make sure I implemented the behavior as expected. Right now the unit test is tightly coupled to the implementation and what my understanding of OpenSSL's code is doing. Table selection function select_w5 is 35% faster than before (AND/OR combination), making P-256
ECDH, ECDSA Sign and ECDSA Verify faster by
2%, 3.7% and 1%, respectively.

| P-256, GV2   | Before (Ops/s) | After (MB/s) | Improvement |
:--------------|---------------:|-------------:|:------------:
| ECDH         |      6019      |     6140     |    1.02x    |
| ECDSA Sign   |     19028      |    19732     |    1.037x   |
| ECDSA Verify |      6595      |     6656     |    1.01x    |

`BIT` is one of the instructions that can be guaranteed to be constant-time by the DIT setting as per https://developer.arm.com/documentation/ddi0595/2021-06/AArch64-Registers/DIT--Data-Independent-Timing.', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/598458acb63859d177f37f0cb0d6a22ce6c66717'}, {'sha': 'f2d14008d4fd461e03baa0b78c1db638f8b21b49', 'author': {'email': 'sachiang@amazon.com', 'name': 'Samuel Chiang'}, 'message': 'Add device farm permissions for android CI (#461)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/f2d14008d4fd461e03baa0b78c1db638f8b21b49'}, {'sha': 'fcd770f2cd24e439dc1bcbf4e5e11b4d675eca4d', 'author': {'email': 'sachiang@amazon.com', 'name': 'Samuel Chiang'}, 'message': 'Upgrade Android CI to use larger instance (#463)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/fcd770f2cd24e439dc1bcbf4e5e11b4d675eca4d'}, {'sha': '98da1e32b1bbeababa3c0b9a9982bf1c82b27eb3', 'author': {'email': '25055813+dkostic@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'dkostic'}, 'message': "Add support for secp256k1 elliptic curve (#457)

The change adds support for secp256k1 elliptic curve (required by ACCP).
We use the generic |EC_GFp_mont_method| for the new curve.

The largest part of the change is adding tests to cover as much as
possible the potential use of the curve. We have added EC, ECDH, and
ECDSA tests. In all three cases we generate the test vectors by newly
added Go scripts. The standard Go library doesn't have support for
secp256k1, and moreover, we can't instantiate the curve on our own
because Go's implementation assumes a curve given by y^2 = x^3 + ax + b
has a = -3, which is not the case for secp256k1. We work around this
issue by using the most widely used secp256k1 Go implementation,
Ethereum's go-ethereum/crypto/secp256k1 module. Also, EVP Wycheproof
tests specific to secp256k1 were added.

A small issue with FIPS service indicator test for ECDH is also fixed.
The test assumed in one case that the indicator should always return
APPROVED, when in reality the indicator status should depened on which
elliptic curve is used in the protocol. For example, when a non FIPS
approved curve like secp256k1 is used, we expect the indicator to
return NOT_APPROVED.

Co-authored-by: Dusan Kostic <dkostic@amazon.com>", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/98da1e32b1bbeababa3c0b9a9982bf1c82b27eb3'}, {'sha': 'a30c797789f5b416fca9d4aaddfafbfc176b3203', 'author': {'email': 'childw@amazon.com', 'name': 'Will Childs-Klein'}, 'message': 'Detect ACCP keys when parsing RSA private keys from ASN.1/DER (#436)

* Detect ACCP keys when parsing RSA private keys from ASN.1/DER

Prior to this change, all RSA private keys were also validated as public
keys during ASN.1 decoding. That was all well and good for CRT-enabled
private keys, as they contained the public exponent `e`, but was not
suitable for stripped private keys (i.e. keys defined only by `n` and
`d`) as required by the JCA and ACCP.

The refactor is based directly on @htorben's sketch [here][1], and does
not change AWS-LC's external API at all. We intentionally attempt to
minimize behavior and validation changes in order to minimize risk of
accidentally impacting RSA key generation and validation. To that end,
we only perform ACCP-aware validation when parsing from DER, and not
when doing key generation or general validation. The relevant RFC
([RFC-8107][2]) does not seem to explicitly permit omitted (i.e. NULL
type [ASN.1 tag value][3] of 5) RSA parameters when parsing RSA private
keys, so we consider an INTEGER value of 0 to indicate that a parameter
is missing in cases pertaining to ACCP.

This change resolves i/CryptoAlg-1026.

[1]: https://github.com/torben-hansen/aws-lc/compare/main...thoughts_rsa_accp_key_check
[2]: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8017#appendix-A.1.2
[3]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X.690#Identifier_octets

* Only check for NULL once parsed, detect ACCP via CRT params

This commit addresses feedback from @apetcher around having multiple
notions of "absent" in the same portions of RSA code. This commit
tightens that up by only considering `0` as "absent" in the DER/ASN.1
parsing code and only considering `NULL` as "absent" in the actual RSA
implementation code. See the test comment and prior commit message for
more detail around this.

Additionally, we now check _all_ RSA params (exponents, modulus and its
factors, and the CRT params) when detecting ACCP keys and adjust the
tests accordingly.

* Update crypto/rsa_extra/rsa_asn1.c

Co-authored-by: dkostic <25055813+dkostic@users.noreply.github.com>

* Refer to JCA instead ACCP

'https://api.github.com/users/dougch/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "### Issues:

Partially Resolves https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/issues/3262

### Description of changes: 

While trying to internalize aws-lc into libs2n.so, we have observed that while symbols aren't hidden in static builds, once objcopy copies libcrypto, the fact that symbols are marked hidden is still honored in the shared lib.  This means libcrypto symbols aren't available (see the issue).

This change makes symbols visible for the aws-lc static.

+// Helper macro for the callback to determine whether an operator expects a len
+// parameter or not
+#define HAS_LEN_OPER(o) ((o) == BIO_CB_READ || (o) == BIO_CB_WRITE || \
+                        (o) == BIO_CB_GETS)
+
+#define HAS_CALLBACK(b) ((b)->callback != NULL || (b)->callback_ex != NULL)
+
+// Helper function to work out whether to call the new style callback or the old
+// one, and translate between the two. Prefer calling the new |callback_ex| over
+// |callback|. This has a long return type for consistency with the old callback.
+// Similarly, for the "long" used for "bio_ret"
+static long call_correct_bio_callback(BIO *b, int oper, const char *argp,
+                                  size_t len, int argi, long argl, long bio_ret,
+                                  size_t *processed) {
+  if (b->callback_ex != NULL) {
+    return b->callback_ex(b, oper, argp, len, argi, argl, bio_ret, processed);
+  }
+
+  // Strip off any BIO_CB_RETURN flag
+  int bareoper = oper & ~BIO_CB_RETURN;
+
+  // We have an old style callback, so we will have to do nasty casts and
+  // check for overflows.
+  if (HAS_LEN_OPER(bareoper)) {
+    // In this case |len| is set, and should be used instead of |argi|
+    if (len > INT_MAX) {
+      return -1;

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Resolves CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
This adds support for legacy `callback`s and newer `callback_ex`s in `BIO_read`, `BIO_write`, and `BIO_free`. These callbacks provide the same API as OpenSSL 1.1.1 and 3.0.0 with the same semantics.

### Callouts
I'm not sure if reusing the logic in `call_bio_callback_with_processed` is helping or hurting the readability. I'm interested in feedback if it people prefer keeping that logic in `BIO_read` and `BIO_write`.

### Testing:
I created a simple mock callback to test this. I am looking for any better examples to make sure I implemented the behavior as expected. Right now the unit test is tightly coupled to the implementation and what my understanding of OpenSSL's code is doing. [bio.h](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/include/openssl/bio.h.in), [bio_lib.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/crypto/bio/bio_lib.c), and [docs](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man3.0/man3/BIO_set_callback_ex.html) for reference.

Resolves CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
This adds support for legacy `callback`s and newer `callback_ex`s in `BIO_read`, `BIO_write`, and `BIO_free`. These callbacks provide the same API as OpenSSL 1.1.1 and 3.0.0 with the same semantics.

### Callouts
I'm not sure if reusing the logic in `call_bio_callback_with_processed` is helping or hurting the readability. I'm interested in feedback if it people prefer keeping that logic in `BIO_read` and `BIO_write`.

### Testing:
I created a simple mock callback to test this. I am looking for any better examples to make sure I implemented the behavior as expected. Right now the unit test is tightly coupled to the implementation and what my understanding of OpenSSL's code is doing. [bio.h](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/include/openssl/bio.h.in), [bio_lib.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/crypto/bio/bio_lib.c), and [docs](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man3.0/man3/BIO_set_callback_ex.html) for reference.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Resolves CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
This adds support for legacy `callback`s and newer `callback_ex`s in `BIO_read`, `BIO_write`, and `BIO_free`. These callbacks provide the same API as OpenSSL 1.1.1 and 3.0.0 with the same semantics.

### Callouts
I'm not sure if reusing the logic in `call_bio_callback_with_processed` is helping or hurting the readability. I'm interested in feedback if it people prefer keeping that logic in `BIO_read` and `BIO_write`.

### Testing:
I created a simple mock callback to test this. I am looking for any better examples to make sure I implemented the behavior as expected. Right now the unit test is tightly coupled to the implementation and what my understanding of OpenSSL's code is doing. [bio.h](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/include/openssl/bio.h.in), [bio_lib.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/crypto/bio/bio_lib.c), and [docs](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man3.0/man3/BIO_set_callback_ex.html) for reference.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Resolves CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
This adds support for legacy `callback`s and newer `callback_ex`s in `BIO_read`, `BIO_write`, and `BIO_free`. These callbacks provide the same API as OpenSSL 1.1.1 and 3.0.0 with the same semantics.

### Callouts
I'm not sure if reusing the logic in `call_bio_callback_with_processed` is helping or hurting the readability. I'm interested in feedback if it people prefer keeping that logic in `BIO_read` and `BIO_write`.

### Testing:
I created a simple mock callback to test this. I am looking for any better examples to make sure I implemented the behavior as expected. Right now the unit test is tightly coupled to the implementation and what my understanding of OpenSSL's code is doing. [bio.h](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/include/openssl/bio.h.in), [bio_lib.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/crypto/bio/bio_lib.c), and [docs](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man3.0/man3/BIO_set_callback_ex.html) for reference.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

{'push_id': 9666834853, 'size': 6, 'distinct_size': 2, 'ref': 'refs/heads/bio_callback', 'head': '90984d2ff4347840e8013fd9fe3d76c83d0feff4', 'before': '161de8f9925059e829c71eab28569b15d3b9cb2b', 'commits': [{'sha': 'a30c797789f5b416fca9d4aaddfafbfc176b3203', 'author': {'email': 'childw@amazon.com', 'name': 'Will Childs-Klein'}, 'message': 'Detect ACCP keys when parsing RSA private keys from ASN.1/DER (#436)

* Detect ACCP keys when parsing RSA private keys from ASN.1/DER

Prior to this change, all RSA private keys were also validated as public
keys during ASN.1 decoding. That was all well and good for CRT-enabled
private keys, as they contained the public exponent `e`, but was not
suitable for stripped private keys (i.e. keys defined only by `n` and
`d`) as required by the JCA and ACCP.

The refactor is based directly on @htorben's sketch [here][1], and does
not change AWS-LC's external API at all. We intentionally attempt to
minimize behavior and validation changes in order to minimize risk of
accidentally impacting RSA key generation and validation. To that end,
we only perform ACCP-aware validation when parsing from DER, and not
when doing key generation or general validation. The relevant RFC
([RFC-8107][2]) does not seem to explicitly permit omitted (i.e. NULL
type [ASN.1 tag value][3] of 5) RSA parameters when parsing RSA private
keys, so we consider an INTEGER value of 0 to indicate that a parameter
is missing in cases pertaining to ACCP.

This change resolves i/CryptoAlg-1026.

[1]: https://github.com/torben-hansen/aws-lc/compare/main...thoughts_rsa_accp_key_check
[2]: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8017#appendix-A.1.2
[3]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X.690#Identifier_octets

* Only check for NULL once parsed, detect ACCP via CRT params

This commit addresses feedback from @apetcher around having multiple
notions of "absent" in the same portions of RSA code. This commit
tightens that up by only considering `0` as "absent" in the DER/ASN.1
parsing code and only considering `NULL` as "absent" in the actual RSA
implementation code. See the test comment and prior commit message for
more detail around this.

Additionally, we now check _all_ RSA params (exponents, modulus and its
factors, and the CRT params) when detecting ACCP keys and adjust the
tests accordingly.

* Update crypto/rsa_extra/rsa_asn1.c

Co-authored-by: dkostic <25055813+dkostic@users.noreply.github.com>

* Refer to JCA instead ACCP

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

{'push_id': 9638621271, 'size': 3, 'distinct_size': 3, 'ref': 'refs/heads/premain-windows', 'head': '35bd848fd6bc233094fb20db849e8e5262c1487e', 'before': 'a72187d4d6d631ff8660ae39002f3cb8e664241a', 'commits': [{'sha': 'a30c797789f5b416fca9d4aaddfafbfc176b3203', 'author': {'email': 'childw@amazon.com', 'name': 'Will Childs-Klein'}, 'message': 'Detect ACCP keys when parsing RSA private keys from ASN.1/DER (#436)

* Detect ACCP keys when parsing RSA private keys from ASN.1/DER

Prior to this change, all RSA private keys were also validated as public
keys during ASN.1 decoding. That was all well and good for CRT-enabled
private keys, as they contained the public exponent `e`, but was not
suitable for stripped private keys (i.e. keys defined only by `n` and
`d`) as required by the JCA and ACCP.

The refactor is based directly on @htorben's sketch [here][1], and does
not change AWS-LC's external API at all. We intentionally attempt to
minimize behavior and validation changes in order to minimize risk of
accidentally impacting RSA key generation and validation. To that end,
we only perform ACCP-aware validation when parsing from DER, and not
when doing key generation or general validation. The relevant RFC
([RFC-8107][2]) does not seem to explicitly permit omitted (i.e. NULL
type [ASN.1 tag value][3] of 5) RSA parameters when parsing RSA private
keys, so we consider an INTEGER value of 0 to indicate that a parameter
is missing in cases pertaining to ACCP.

This change resolves i/CryptoAlg-1026.

[1]: https://github.com/torben-hansen/aws-lc/compare/main...thoughts_rsa_accp_key_check
[2]: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8017#appendix-A.1.2
[3]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X.690#Identifier_octets

* Only check for NULL once parsed, detect ACCP via CRT params

This commit addresses feedback from @apetcher around having multiple
notions of "absent" in the same portions of RSA code. This commit
tightens that up by only considering `0` as "absent" in the DER/ASN.1
parsing code and only considering `NULL` as "absent" in the actual RSA
implementation code. See the test comment and prior commit message for
more detail around this.

Additionally, we now check _all_ RSA params (exponents, modulus and its
factors, and the CRT params) when detecting ACCP keys and adjust the
tests accordingly.

* Update crypto/rsa_extra/rsa_asn1.c

Co-authored-by: dkostic <25055813+dkostic@users.noreply.github.com>

* Refer to JCA instead ACCP

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

The change adds support for secp256k1 elliptic curve (required by ACCP).
We use the generic |EC_GFp_mont_method| for the new curve.

The largest part of the change is adding tests to cover as much as
possible the potential use of the curve. We have added EC, ECDH, and
ECDSA tests. In all three cases we generate the test vectors by newly
added Go scripts. The standard Go library doesn't have support for
secp256k1, and moreover, we can't instantiate the curve on our own
because Go's implementation assumes a curve given by y^2 = x^3 + ax + b
has a = -3, which is not the case for secp256k1. We work around this
issue by using the most widely used secp256k1 Go implementation,
Ethereum's go-ethereum/crypto/secp256k1 module. Also, EVP Wycheproof
tests specific to secp256k1 were added.

A small issue with FIPS service indicator test for ECDH is also fixed.
The test assumed in one case that the indicator should always return
APPROVED, when in reality the indicator status should depened on which
elliptic curve is used in the protocol. For example, when a non FIPS
approved curve like secp256k1 is used, we expect the indicator to
return NOT_APPROVED.

Co-authored-by: Dusan Kostic <dkostic@amazon.com>", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/98da1e32b1bbeababa3c0b9a9982bf1c82b27eb3'}, {'sha': '198d3c72a51e960d74e9366a2d84429e6bf1b8de', 'author': {'email': 'andhop@amazon.com', 'name': 'Andrew Hopkins'}, 'message': "Merge branch 'main' into premain-windows", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/198d3c72a51e960d74e9366a2d84429e6bf1b8de'}]}

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

The module code uses the linker-added symbols to find the its code and data at run-time and hashes them upon initialisation. The result is compared against a value stored inside `libcrypto.so`, but outside of the module. That value will, initially, be incorrect, but `inject-hash.go` can inject the correct value.
 
+### Windows Shared build
+
+The Shared Windows FIPS integrity test differs in two key ways:
+1. How the start and end of the module are marked
+2. How the correct integrity hash is calculated
+
+Microsoft Visual C compiler (MSVC) does not support linker scripts which add symbols to mark the start and end of the text and rodata sections on Linux. Instead, fips_shared_library_marker.c is compiled twice to generate two object files that contain start/end functions and variables. MSVC `pragma` segment definitions are used to place the markers in specific sections (i.e. `.fipstx$a`). This particular name format uses Portable Executable Grouped Sections to control what section the code is placed and the order within the section. With the start and end markers placed at `$a` and `$z` respectively, BCM puts everything in the `$b` section. When the final crypto.dll is built all the code is in the `.fipstx` section, all data and constants is in `.fipsda`, and everything is in the correct order.
+
+The process to generate the expected integrity fingerprint is also different from Linux:
+1. Build the required object files once: `bcm.obj` from `bcm.c` and the start/end object files
+   1. `bcm.obj` places the power on self tests in the `.CRT$XCU` section which is run automatically by the Windows Common Runtime library (CRT) startup code
+2. Use MSVC's `lib.exe` to combine the start/end object files with `bcm.obj` into `bcm.lib`. Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

The change adds support for secp256k1 elliptic curve (required by ACCP).
We use the generic |EC_GFp_mont_method| for the new curve.

The largest part of the change is adding tests to cover as much as
possible the potential use of the curve. We have added EC, ECDH, and
ECDSA tests. In all three cases we generate the test vectors by newly
added Go scripts. The standard Go library doesn't have support for
secp256k1, and moreover, we can't instantiate the curve on our own
because Go's implementation assumes a curve given by y^2 = x^3 + ax + b
has a = -3, which is not the case for secp256k1. We work around this
issue by using the most widely used secp256k1 Go implementation,
Ethereum's go-ethereum/crypto/secp256k1 module. Also, EVP Wycheproof
tests specific to secp256k1 were added.

A small issue with FIPS service indicator test for ECDH is also fixed.
The test assumed in one case that the indicator should always return
APPROVED, when in reality the indicator status should depened on which
elliptic curve is used in the protocol. For example, when a non FIPS
approved curve like secp256k1 is used, we expect the indicator to
return NOT_APPROVED.

Resolves CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
This adds support for legacy `callback`s and newer `callback_ex`s in `BIO_read`, `BIO_write`, and `BIO_free`. These callbacks provide the same API as OpenSSL 1.1.1 and 3.0.0 with the same semantics.

### Callouts
I'm not sure if reusing the logic in `call_bio_callback_with_processed` is helping or hurting the readability. I'm interested in feedback if it people prefer keeping that logic in `BIO_read` and `BIO_write`.

### Testing:
I created a simple mock callback to test this. I am looking for any better examples to make sure I implemented the behavior as expected. Right now the unit test is tightly coupled to the implementation and what my understanding of OpenSSL's code is doing. [bio.h](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/include/openssl/bio.h.in), [bio_lib.c](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/crypto/bio/bio_lib.c), and [docs](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man3.0/man3/BIO_set_callback_ex.html) for reference.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

{'push_id': 9599800628, 'size': 4, 'distinct_size': 2, 'ref': 'refs/heads/premain-windows', 'head': '78590af9b252d3b95bc0e5c9543f260de1a23b94', 'before': 'c29c15b25aff963907f179f00e3653b0635c9c6c', 'commits': [{'sha': '36ac957b54fada4797f46a6324ecbc3e919c7f20', 'author': {'email': 'andhop@amazon.com', 'name': 'Andrew Hopkins'}, 'message': 'Add support for overriding OPENSSL_realloc and add tests for memory management weak symbols (#456)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/36ac957b54fada4797f46a6324ecbc3e919c7f20'}, {'sha': '8f184f5d69604cc4645bafec47c2d6d9929cb50f', 'author': {'email': '50673096+torben-hansen@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'torben-hansen'}, 'message': "Make it possible to distinguish BSSL and AWS-LC (#458)

OpenSSL_version() can be a convenient method to distinguish AWS-LC from other projects at run-time. But it can't be used as a distinguisher from BSSL without changing the name to AWS-LC. Make this change since AWS-LC is a dependency in projects that can also depend on BSSL.

At the same time, modify the name of the project-specific header file (is_boringssl.h) to an AWS-LC-specific name.", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/8f184f5d69604cc4645bafec47c2d6d9929cb50f'}, {'sha': '598458acb63859d177f37f0cb0d6a22ce6c66717', 'author': {'email': '66388554+nebeid@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Nevine Ebeid'}, 'message': 'Using the BIT instruction in Armv8 table selection. (#452)

Table selection function select_w5 is 35% faster than before (AND/OR combination), making P-256
ECDH, ECDSA Sign and ECDSA Verify faster by
2%, 3.7% and 1%, respectively.

| P-256, GV2   | Before (Ops/s) | After (MB/s) | Improvement |
:--------------|---------------:|-------------:|:------------:
| ECDH         |      6019      |     6140     |    1.02x    |
| ECDSA Sign   |     19028      |    19732     |    1.037x   |
| ECDSA Verify |      6595      |     6656     |    1.01x    |

`BIT` is one of the instructions that can be guaranteed to be constant-time by the DIT setting as per https://developer.arm.com/documentation/ddi0595/2021-06/AArch64-Registers/DIT--Data-Independent-Timing.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/598458acb63859d177f37f0cb0d6a22ce6c66717'}, {'sha': '78590af9b252d3b95bc0e5c9543f260de1a23b94', 'author': {'email': 'andhop@amazon.com', 'name': 'Andrew Hopkins'}, 'message': "Merge branch 'main' into premain-windows", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/78590af9b252d3b95bc0e5c9543f260de1a23b94'}]}

Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

Description:
Creating just a Gerrit password isn't enough.  Before you can push a
change to Gerrit, you must also create/associate a Gerrit account with
the google account used to create the password.

This avoids "git push ..." rejections like this:

  remote: PERMISSION_DENIED: The caller does not have permission
  remote: [type.googleapis.com/google.rpc.LocalizedMessage]
  remote: locale: "en-US"
  remote: message: "\'git push\' requires a Gerrit user account."

Bug: 476
Change-Id: I41ca408706d0d0c5bb22006f4c31d51fc1267f69
Reviewed-on: https://boringssl-review.googlesource.com/c/boringssl/+/51165
Commit-Queue: David Benjamin <davidben@google.com>
Reviewed-by: Adam Langley <agl@google.com>
Commit-Queue: Adam Langley <agl@google.com>', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/0f4454c07545e6f4465ad88e83fcbaa95a08d28f'}, {'sha': '0fc57bef1821c163ac023a0aa96e4fb2a67c0d82', 'author': {'email': 'muir.james.a@gmail.com', 'name': 'James Muir'}, 'message': 'Simpler square-root computation for Ed25519

Description:
Mark Wooden and Franck Rondepierre noted that the square-root-mod-p
operations used in the EdDSA RFC (RFC 8032) can be simplified.  For
Ed25519, instead of computing u*v^3 * (u * v^7)^((p-5)/8), we can
compute u * (u*v)^((p-5)/8).  This saves 3 multiplications and 2
squarings.  For more details (including a proof), see the following
message from the CFRG mailing list:

  https://mailarchive.ietf.org/arch/msg/cfrg/qlKpMBqxXZYmDpXXIx6LO3Oznv4/

Testing:
Build and run the Ed25519 tests:

  mkdir build
  cd build
  cmake -GNinja ..
  ninja && ./crypto/crypto_test --gtest_filter="Ed25519Test*"

Numerical testing of the square-root computation can be done using the
following sage script:

  def legendre(x,p):
      return kronecker(x,p)

  # Ed25519
  p = 2**255-19
  # -1 is a square
  if legendre(-1,p)==1:
      print("-1 is a square")
  # 2 is a non-square
  if legendre(2,p)==-1:
      print("2 is a non-square")

  # 2 is a generator
  # this can be checked by factoring p-1
  # and then showing 2**((p-1)/q) != 1 (mod p)
  # for all primes q dividing p-1.

  # suppose u/v is a square.
  # to compute one of its square roots, find x such that
  #    x**4 == (u/v)**2 .
  # this implies
  #    x**2 ==  u/v, or
  #    x**2 == -(u/v) ,
  # which implies either x or i*x is a square-root of u/v (where i is a square root of -1).
  # we can take x equal to u * (u*v)**((p-5)/8).

  g = 2
  s = p>>2  # s = (p-1)/4
  i = power_mod(g, s, p)

  t = p>>3  # t = (p-5)/8
  COUNT = 1<<18
  while COUNT > 0:
      COUNT -= 1

      r = randint(0,p-1)   # r = u/v
      v = randint(1,p-1)
      u = mod(r*v,p)

      # compute x = u * (u*v)**((p-5)/8)
      w = mod(u*v,p)
      x = mod(u*power_mod(w, t, p), p)

      # check that x**2 == r, or (i*x)**2 == r, or r is not a square
      rr = power_mod(x, 2, p)
      if rr==r:
          continue

      rr = power_mod(mod(i*x,p), 2, p)
      if rr==r:
          continue

      if legendre(r,p) != 1:
          continue

      print("failure!")
      exit()

  print("passed!")

Commit-Queue: Adam Langley <agl@google.com>', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/0fc57bef1821c163ac023a0aa96e4fb2a67c0d82'}, {'sha': '7198d1132bc194b360c37b05b9a82f6231533114', 'author': {'email': 'davidben@google.com', 'name': 'David Benjamin'}, 'message': "Explicitly reject self-referential ech_outer_extensions.

The ECH extension is not covered in the AAD and so should not be
referenced in ech_outer_extensions. We end up rejecting this anyway when
checking for valid ClientHelloInners, but better to reject this
explicitly, as the spec suggests.

As part of this, use the more specific error in the various tests, so we
can distinguish the two cases. (DECODE_ERROR is coming from an extra,
probably unnecessary, error in ssl_decode_client_hello_inner's caller.)

Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

Description:
Creating just a Gerrit password isn't enough.  Before you can push a
change to Gerrit, you must also create/associate a Gerrit account with
the google account used to create the password.

This avoids "git push ..." rejections like this:

  remote: PERMISSION_DENIED: The caller does not have permission
  remote: [type.googleapis.com/google.rpc.LocalizedMessage]
  remote: locale: "en-US"
  remote: message: "\'git push\' requires a Gerrit user account."

This is designed to be the minimal infrastructure required to support
using BoringSSL in the Rust ecosystem without fear of ABI drift. Bindgen
is used to generate Rust bindings in lockstep with the rest of the
build. `rust-openssl` can consume these generated bindings with minimal
changes.

Commit-Queue: Adam Langley <agl@google.com>', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/0f4454c07545e6f4465ad88e83fcbaa95a08d28f'}, {'sha': '0fc57bef1821c163ac023a0aa96e4fb2a67c0d82', 'author': {'email': 'muir.james.a@gmail.com', 'name': 'James Muir'}, 'message': 'Simpler square-root computation for Ed25519

Description:
Mark Wooden and Franck Rondepierre noted that the square-root-mod-p
operations used in the EdDSA RFC (RFC 8032) can be simplified.  For
Ed25519, instead of computing u*v^3 * (u * v^7)^((p-5)/8), we can
compute u * (u*v)^((p-5)/8).  This saves 3 multiplications and 2
squarings.  For more details (including a proof), see the following
message from the CFRG mailing list:

  https://mailarchive.ietf.org/arch/msg/cfrg/qlKpMBqxXZYmDpXXIx6LO3Oznv4/

Testing:
Build and run the Ed25519 tests:

  mkdir build
  cd build
  cmake -GNinja ..
  ninja && ./crypto/crypto_test --gtest_filter="Ed25519Test*"

Numerical testing of the square-root computation can be done using the
following sage script:

  def legendre(x,p):
      return kronecker(x,p)

  # Ed25519
  p = 2**255-19
  # -1 is a square
  if legendre(-1,p)==1:
      print("-1 is a square")
  # 2 is a non-square
  if legendre(2,p)==-1:
      print("2 is a non-square")

  # 2 is a generator
  # this can be checked by factoring p-1
  # and then showing 2**((p-1)/q) != 1 (mod p)
  # for all primes q dividing p-1.

  # suppose u/v is a square.
  # to compute one of its square roots, find x such that
  #    x**4 == (u/v)**2 .
  # this implies
  #    x**2 ==  u/v, or
  #    x**2 == -(u/v) ,
  # which implies either x or i*x is a square-root of u/v (where i is a square root of -1).
  # we can take x equal to u * (u*v)**((p-5)/8).

  g = 2
  s = p>>2  # s = (p-1)/4
  i = power_mod(g, s, p)

  t = p>>3  # t = (p-5)/8
  COUNT = 1<<18
  while COUNT > 0:
      COUNT -= 1

      r = randint(0,p-1)   # r = u/v
      v = randint(1,p-1)
      u = mod(r*v,p)

      # compute x = u * (u*v)**((p-5)/8)
      w = mod(u*v,p)
      x = mod(u*power_mod(w, t, p), p)

      # check that x**2 == r, or (i*x)**2 == r, or r is not a square
      rr = power_mod(x, 2, p)
      if rr==r:
          continue

      rr = power_mod(mod(i*x,p), 2, p)
      if rr==r:
          continue

      if legendre(r,p) != 1:
          continue

      print("failure!")
      exit()

  print("passed!")

Bug: 476
Change-Id: I41ca408706d0d0c5bb22006f4c31d51fc1267f69
Reviewed-on: https://boringssl-review.googlesource.com/c/boringssl/+/51165
Commit-Queue: David Benjamin <davidben@google.com>
Reviewed-by: Adam Langley <agl@google.com>
Commit-Queue: Adam Langley <agl@google.com>', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/0f4454c07545e6f4465ad88e83fcbaa95a08d28f'}, {'sha': '0fc57bef1821c163ac023a0aa96e4fb2a67c0d82', 'author': {'email': 'muir.james.a@gmail.com', 'name': 'James Muir'}, 'message': 'Simpler square-root computation for Ed25519

Description:
Mark Wooden and Franck Rondepierre noted that the square-root-mod-p
operations used in the EdDSA RFC (RFC 8032) can be simplified.  For
Ed25519, instead of computing u*v^3 * (u * v^7)^((p-5)/8), we can
compute u * (u*v)^((p-5)/8).  This saves 3 multiplications and 2
squarings.  For more details (including a proof), see the following
message from the CFRG mailing list:

  https://mailarchive.ietf.org/arch/msg/cfrg/qlKpMBqxXZYmDpXXIx6LO3Oznv4/

Testing:
Build and run the Ed25519 tests:

  mkdir build
  cd build
  cmake -GNinja ..
  ninja && ./crypto/crypto_test --gtest_filter="Ed25519Test*"

Numerical testing of the square-root computation can be done using the
following sage script:

  def legendre(x,p):
      return kronecker(x,p)

  # Ed25519
  p = 2**255-19
  # -1 is a square
  if legendre(-1,p)==1:
      print("-1 is a square")
  # 2 is a non-square
  if legendre(2,p)==-1:
      print("2 is a non-square")

  # 2 is a generator
  # this can be checked by factoring p-1
  # and then showing 2**((p-1)/q) != 1 (mod p)
  # for all primes q dividing p-1.

  # suppose u/v is a square.
  # to compute one of its square roots, find x such that
  #    x**4 == (u/v)**2 .
  # this implies
  #    x**2 ==  u/v, or
  #    x**2 == -(u/v) ,
  # which implies either x or i*x is a square-root of u/v (where i is a square root of -1).
  # we can take x equal to u * (u*v)**((p-5)/8).

  g = 2
  s = p>>2  # s = (p-1)/4
  i = power_mod(g, s, p)

  t = p>>3  # t = (p-5)/8
  COUNT = 1<<18
  while COUNT > 0:
      COUNT -= 1

      r = randint(0,p-1)   # r = u/v
      v = randint(1,p-1)
      u = mod(r*v,p)

      # compute x = u * (u*v)**((p-5)/8)
      w = mod(u*v,p)
      x = mod(u*power_mod(w, t, p), p)

      # check that x**2 == r, or (i*x)**2 == r, or r is not a square
      rr = power_mod(x, 2, p)
      if rr==r:
          continue

      rr = power_mod(mod(i*x,p), 2, p)
      if rr==r:
          continue

      if legendre(r,p) != 1:
          continue

      print("failure!")
      exit()

  print("passed!")

Linux and macOS platforms on architectures where we don't build

atomics these days, so the flag is only useful if you want to force it.

Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

Addresses CryptoAlg-953

### Description of changes: 
Customers can already control most heap memory allocation inside AWS-LC. `OPENSSL_realloc` uses functions that can be overwritten, but it is still opinionated about how realloc should work. This change adds support to define a custom realloc function. This also adds a test for using these weak symbols which is a little cumbersome from C++.

### Callouts
I had to make a new test executable since the way the weak symbols work it overrides it for the entire process. We may want to consider adding support to set these as callback functions like [s2n-tls](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/blob/main/utils/s2n_mem.c#L133-L149) which would be easier to test and debug.

### Testing:
Existing unit tests pass and new unit test works and is run by default.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

This starts a new section "p521" devoted to special optimizations
related to the NIST P-521 curve, where the underlying field has
characteristic 2^521 - 1, a Mersenne prime. The function
bignum_add_p521 is modular addition w.r.t. this prime, by analogy with
the existing bignum_add_p256 and bignum_add_p384 functions.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/2d5bb1d29303516d20ab222f5405ebbe2e83d993', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AWSjswinney/aws-lc/commits/7576a2db2283a7c5aec5e4999210c4a0b81e1df9'}, {'sha': 'be05ceb8e361ad70446c49d8fbc4ad22996f3687', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Standardize numeric literals in ARM code to use # symbol

The code previously had a mix of cases where the "#" prefix was
used before numeric literals and cases where it wasn't. It makes
no difference to gcc or the GNU assembler (and hence this change
does not alter the object files or the proofs) but this makes
things more consistent and may help other tools processing the
ARM asm files.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/cba7bcb9557dd0238674b603a97a4941ca130c95', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AWSjswinney/aws-lc/commits/7878c353752fdb1da605e7522b8f30a8116cb3c9'}, {'sha': '828c1b0ce052ad902a79adb7130fe4e23215ee45', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Regularize .text and other directives

This makes sure each .S file has an explicit .text directive, and
also regularizes the positioning of these and the .globl ones (plus
the .intel_syntax ones for x86), collecting them at the beginning
just after the initial API comment banner. The only even slightly
non-trivial change is the removal of the global directive for
bignum_of_word_nontrivial in "x86/generic/bignum_of_word.S"
(this was not present for ARM, nor was it declared in the header).
There are no changes to code and hence no changes in the proofs.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/debfd4cbdd1db43c1df861dc185d07551b2503eb', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AWSjswinney/aws-lc/commits/828c1b0ce052ad902a79adb7130fe4e23215ee45'}, {'sha': '11f9fbb3008e3507561991f82a7226555bec99e2', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add non-executable stack directives to all asm files

This appends the following additional directive at the end of each
assembler file, so that the .o produced doesn't appear to need
executable stack:

  #if defined(__linux__) && defined(__ELF__)
  .section .note.GNU-stack,"",%progbits
  #endif

This follows the guidance here:

  https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki/Hardened/GNU_stack_quickstart#Patching

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/bac30724f87c03e8851c119fd583d3e429e8027e', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AWSjswinney/aws-lc/commits/11f9fbb3008e3507561991f82a7226555bec99e2'}, {'sha': 'a8e3b92237dd5c190dd3b3bb80d445a2bafcd5f6', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Switch P-256 and P-384 code from assembler macros to C preprocessor

This is a superficial but syntactically messy change to avoid use of
the assembler .macro construct in the P-256 and P-384 functions, for
both ARM and x86 (so now macros are only used in the "fastmul"
functions), replaced by use of the C preprocessor. This is intended to
ease a FIPS build of the code, but does have the side-effect that
preprocessed code can now have multiple instructions per line
separated by semicolons. This is unproblematic for gcc or the GNU
assembler.

Took the chance to make one trivial but semantically meaningful
change, slightly tweaking x86/p384/bignum_tomont_p384.S in line with
earlier changes to the Montgomery multiplication to shorten the code a
bit and keep the identically-named "macros" the same.

Numeric constants from "#define" and assembler-level values
from ".set" are now always uppercase. This makes it easier to parse
the assembler files in a context-free way for scripting purposes.
This does not change the text section of any object file and hence
does not require proof changes. However the .set directives do
add a symbol to the symbol table, and those have changed in the
following from "i" to "I":

        arm/fastmul/bignum_kmul_16_32.o
        arm/fastmul/bignum_kmul_32_64.o
        arm/fastmul/bignum_ksqr_16_32.o
        arm/fastmul/bignum_ksqr_32_64.o
        arm/p256/bignum_mux_4.o
        arm/p384/bignum_mux_6.o
        arm/p521/bignum_double_p521.o
        x86/fastmul/bignum_kmul_32_64.o
        x86/fastmul/bignum_ksqr_16_32.o
        x86/fastmul/bignum_ksqr_32_64.o
        x86/p256/bignum_mux_4.o
        x86/p384/bignum_mux_6.o
        x86/p521/bignum_double_p521.o

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/e564707bda566b7ce8482d0134a58cce899a0636', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AWSjswinney/aws-lc/commits/bd990d9815dd9432f31ea4eb72c61388c18361e3'}, {'sha': '9647c4d1e9c47b4f94a84b8ab422897014812541', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add P-521 Montgomery squaring

This is just plain modular squaring (as in bignum_sqr_p521) followed
by a rotation to make it into a Montgomery operation with base
2^{9*64} = 2^576 based on the native size of nine 64-bit digits. The
benefit of using a Montgomery representation is not clear in the case of
a Mersenne prime (or put another way, the basic modular operations
already are Montgomery operations to base 2^521) but it seems worth
having the usual suite of operations for compatibility.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/c89ae508fcdfdf649b750dced69c182b85054a71', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/AWSjswinney/aws-lc/commits/5ea515ab567aaea412cb2366b1b18c1cd3bcbbca'}, {'sha': '20959a46b1d1a71b45f011e83b172f6a7d206c1c', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add AT&T syntax versions of x86 P-384 functions

The new files (x86_att/p384/*.S) are generated from the Intel syntax
originals (x86/p384/*.S) using a simple sed script. The generated
files are kept in this repo, but can be removed with "make clobber"
and regenerated with "make code" (in the new x86_att directory). This
translation process is not in general robust, only being intended to
handle this very restricted set of files. Even here, the translation
process runs a sanity check during generation to make sure each Intel
syntax original and its AT&T translation result in exactly the same
object file when assembled with the GNU assembler.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds depends on the change in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434 and is easier to review once it is merged in. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

{'push_id': 9550168970, 'size': 1, 'distinct_size': 0, 'ref': 'refs/heads/main', 'head': 'da2d67fa5fea7481707762079bba455805e91f26', 'before': 'e5f72ab1c9611466d347fff615503a3bf7248fcc', 'commits': [{'sha': 'da2d67fa5fea7481707762079bba455805e91f26', 'author': {'email': 'sachiang@amazon.com', 'name': 'Samuel Chiang'}, 'message': "Add Android cross-compilation CI dimension with `AWSLCAndroidTestRunner`  (#448)

This change adds a new codebuild batch for android builds 
`Static`, `Shared`, `Debug`, `Release`, and `FIPS`. It also
adds the `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` flag which compiles our test
executables into `so` executables when it's on. Only Shared 
Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app
with the right execution permissions, so test executable
outputs need to be outputted as an `so` for our
`AWSLCAndroidTestRunner` app to be able to execute the tests
within the app dimension.
The yml files under `tests/ci/codebuild/android/` were split
into 5 dimensions for each build, so we can parallelize the
Device Farm runs once the Device Farm functionality is turned
on.", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/da2d67fa5fea7481707762079bba455805e91f26'}]}

* AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly 
on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's 
`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`, this mini Android test harness is
 intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm.
 The tests will include crypto_test, urandom_test, decrepit_test
and ssl_test, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that 
builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains,
mitigating past issues like this: 
https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

* ANDROIDTESTRUNNER is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC 
that compiles our test executables from regular executables to 
so executables when ANDROIDTESTRUNNER is on. Only Shared 
Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app 
with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs 
need to be outputted as an so for AWSLCAndroidTestRunner to be
 able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual ANDROIDTESTRUNNER change in AWS-LC is not in this

Use PAuth as defined by BoringSSL in P256 AArch64 code as applied to OpenSSL in
https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/19e277dd19f2897f6a7b7eb236abe46655e575bf#diff-7702bd248b6e21dbdbeeb64dd3aba22e8f7addff40d841ff2abaf58faf2efc18

**Notes:**
- `scatter` and `gather` functions in OpenSSL are not used in AWS-LC.
- `ecp_niszt256_add` funtion was removed from assembly in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/commit/d60b60e8e5f7eb8e5ca76190246f7fe17d95f9e1.
  It is not used in the critical path of computation and it's defined in p256-nistz.c in terms of the assembly function `ecp_nistz256_point_add`.
- The same is done to the code we added in `p256_beeu-armv8-asm.pl`.

It can be tested by adding the following in crypto/fipsmodule/CMakeLists.txt:
```
target_compile_options(fipsmodule PRIVATE -mbranch-protection=standard)
```

* Simplified the Benchmarking framework

The benchmarking framework was complex and that led to difficulty
debugging issues, and eventually led to the discontinuation of it's
usage. This change simplifies the framework to provide easier debugging
as well as fixing some issues

Specifically this:
1) Moves the benchmarking framework to run directly on CodeBuild
2) Changes how regressions are calculated to use a more well-behaved statistic
3) Reduces testing time and parallelism in tests to ideally get more consistent results
4) Fixes an unrelated bug that caused builds with testing disabled to fail
5) Makes minor adjustments to build parameters
6) Removes OpenSSL and BoringSSL from the automatic benchmarks, since they are out of our control and will likely cause regular spurious failures", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/7d2dd75b0becbc7538292816823f56950a70c585'}, {'sha': 'eb93f37131586e86ec2a2fad17e67ef9a4b9fcea', 'author': {'email': '65570357+bryce-shang@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Bryce Shang'}, 'message': 'Fix compiler error reported by gcc-4.1. {'push_id': 9535922145, 'size': 5, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/main', 'head': 'e5f72ab1c9611466d347fff615503a3bf7248fcc', 'before': '25ec1b6d4e91faf6d9e64dd479211bb759cd0c78', 'commits': [{'sha': 'a83f5ddd79e4769667fc283e3270170608814972', 'author': {'email': '66388554+nebeid@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Nevine Ebeid'}, 'message': "Update P-256 AArch64 code to use PAuth as defined by BoringSSL (#415)

Use PAuth as defined by BoringSSL in P256 AArch64 code as applied to OpenSSL in
https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/19e277dd19f2897f6a7b7eb236abe46655e575bf#diff-7702bd248b6e21dbdbeeb64dd3aba22e8f7addff40d841ff2abaf58faf2efc18

**Notes:**
- `scatter` and `gather` functions in OpenSSL are not used in AWS-LC.
- `ecp_niszt256_add` funtion was removed from assembly in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/commit/d60b60e8e5f7eb8e5ca76190246f7fe17d95f9e1.
  It is not used in the critical path of computation and it's defined in p256-nistz.c in terms of the assembly function `ecp_nistz256_point_add`.
- The same is done to the code we added in `p256_beeu-armv8-asm.pl`.

It can be tested by adding the following in crypto/fipsmodule/CMakeLists.txt:
```
target_compile_options(fipsmodule PRIVATE -mbranch-protection=standard)
```

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change makes the logic to build libcrypto a separate function that takes a list of objects and static libraries to build it from. This change maintains the current behavior and only builds one libcrypto. The proposed design in CryptoAlg-907 and implemented in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433 uses this logic to build a lib_precrypto that generates the correct integrity fingerprint in a second fipsmodule to build the real libcrypto.

### Call-outs:
This is a draft while ironing out the design and implementation in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433. I am currently going with this approach due to a potential limitation of  [debug/pe](https://pkg.go.dev/debug/pe) and/or the way we build libcrypto. The issue is getting the position of the symbols in crypto.dll from debug/pe. More details in CryptoAlg-907.

### Testing:
This change was tested in isolation and as a part of https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433 with a complete end to end flow for the WIndows FIPS build.

(#446)

* Remove HMAC select check.

* Bump CI.', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/0f5a1a0e6e95f9fc9ef4b512875f5b2d72b6ff07'}, {'sha': '25ec1b6d4e91faf6d9e64dd479211bb759cd0c78', 'author': {'email': 'sachiang@amazon.com', 'name': 'Samuel Chiang'}, 'message': "Add Android test harness for AWS-LC (#389)

* AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly 
on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's 
`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`, this mini Android test harness is
 intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm.
 The tests will include crypto_test, urandom_test, decrepit_test
and ssl_test, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that 
builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains,
mitigating past issues like this: 
https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

* ANDROIDTESTRUNNER is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC 
that compiles our test executables from regular executables to 
so executables when ANDROIDTESTRUNNER is on. Only Shared 
Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app 
with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs 
need to be outputted as an so for AWSLCAndroidTestRunner to be
 able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual ANDROIDTESTRUNNER change in AWS-LC is not in this 
PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/25ec1b6d4e91faf6d9e64dd479211bb759cd0c78'}, {'sha': 'a83f5ddd79e4769667fc283e3270170608814972', 'author': {'email': '66388554+nebeid@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Nevine Ebeid'}, 'message': "Update P-256 AArch64 code to use PAuth as defined by BoringSSL (#415)

Use PAuth as defined by BoringSSL in P256 AArch64 code as applied to OpenSSL in
https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/19e277dd19f2897f6a7b7eb236abe46655e575bf#diff-7702bd248b6e21dbdbeeb64dd3aba22e8f7addff40d841ff2abaf58faf2efc18

**Notes:**
- `scatter` and `gather` functions in OpenSSL are not used in AWS-LC.
- `ecp_niszt256_add` funtion was removed from assembly in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/commit/d60b60e8e5f7eb8e5ca76190246f7fe17d95f9e1.
  It is not used in the critical path of computation and it's defined in p256-nistz.c in terms of the assembly function `ecp_nistz256_point_add`.
- The same is done to the code we added in `p256_beeu-armv8-asm.pl`.

It can be tested by adding the following in crypto/fipsmodule/CMakeLists.txt:
```
target_compile_options(fipsmodule PRIVATE -mbranch-protection=standard)
```

Co-authored-by: Bryce Shang <65570357+bryce-shang@users.noreply.github.com>', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/f6614260186c1b437ae54406fcb9b7f0736b154b'}, {'sha': '7d2dd75b0becbc7538292816823f56950a70c585', 'author': {'email': 'domdams@amazon.com', 'name': 'Dominic Dams'}, 'message': "Simplified the Benchmarking framework (#435)

* Simplified the Benchmarking framework

The benchmarking framework was complex and that led to difficulty
debugging issues, and eventually led to the discontinuation of it's
usage. This change simplifies the framework to provide easier debugging
as well as fixing some issues

Specifically this:
1) Moves the benchmarking framework to run directly on CodeBuild
2) Changes how regressions are calculated to use a more well-behaved statistic
3) Reduces testing time and parallelism in tests to ideally get more consistent results
4) Fixes an unrelated bug that caused builds with testing disabled to fail
5) Makes minor adjustments to build parameters
6) Removes OpenSSL and BoringSSL from the automatic benchmarks, since they are out of our control and will likely cause regular spurious failures", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/7d2dd75b0becbc7538292816823f56950a70c585'}, {'sha': 'eb93f37131586e86ec2a2fad17e67ef9a4b9fcea', 'author': {'email': '65570357+bryce-shang@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Bryce Shang'}, 'message': 'Fix compiler error reported by gcc-4.1. ```

```

authentication. This commit https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/19e277dd19f2897f6a7b7eb236abe46655e575bf updated them to use the same macros defined in BoringSSL.
This PR applies the changes to the code in AWS-LC.
Notes:
- Notes:
- `scatter` and `gather` functions in OpenSSL are not used in AWS-LC.
- `ecp_niszt256_add` funtion was removed from assembly in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/commit/d60b60e8e5f7eb8e5ca76190246f7fe17d95f9e1.
  It is not used in the critical path of computation and it's defined in p256-nistz.c in terms of the assembly function `ecp_nistz256_point_add`.
- The same is done to the code we added in `p256_beeu-armv8-asm.pl`.
