* Remove HMAC select check.

* Bump CI.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/0f5a1a0e6e95f9fc9ef4b512875f5b2d72b6ff07'}, {'sha': '25ec1b6d4e91faf6d9e64dd479211bb759cd0c78', 'author': {'email': 'sachiang@amazon.com', 'name': 'Samuel Chiang'}, 'message': "Add Android test harness for AWS-LC (#389)

* AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly 
on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's 
`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`, this mini Android test harness is
 intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm.
 The tests will include crypto_test, urandom_test, decrepit_test
and ssl_test, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that 
builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains,
mitigating past issues like this: 
https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

* ANDROIDTESTRUNNER is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC 
that compiles our test executables from regular executables to 
so executables when ANDROIDTESTRUNNER is on. Only Shared 
Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app 
with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs 
need to be outputted as an so for AWSLCAndroidTestRunner to be
 able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual ANDROIDTESTRUNNER change in AWS-LC is not in this 
PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/25ec1b6d4e91faf6d9e64dd479211bb759cd0c78'}]}

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change makes the logic to build libcrypto a separate function that takes a list of objects and static libraries to build it from. This change maintains the current behavior and only builds one libcrypto. The proposed design in CryptoAlg-907 and implemented in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433 uses this logic to build a lib_precrypto that generates the correct integrity fingerprint in a second fipsmodule to build the real libcrypto.

### Call-outs:
This is a draft while ironing out the design and implementation in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433. I am currently going with this approach due to a potential limitation of  [debug/pe](https://pkg.go.dev/debug/pe) and/or the way we build libcrypto. The issue is getting the position of the symbols in crypto.dll from debug/pe. More details in CryptoAlg-907.

### Testing:
This change was tested in isolation and as a part of https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433 with a complete end to end flow for the WIndows FIPS build.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change makes the logic to build libcrypto a separate function that takes a list of objects and static libraries to build it from. This change maintains the current behavior and only builds one libcrypto. The proposed design in CryptoAlg-907 and implemented in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433 uses this logic to build a lib_precrypto that generates the correct integrity fingerprint in a second fipsmodule to build the real libcrypto.

### Call-outs:
This is a draft while ironing out the design and implementation in https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433. I am currently going with this approach due to a potential limitation of  [debug/pe](https://pkg.go.dev/debug/pe) and/or the way we build libcrypto. The issue is getting the position of the symbols in crypto.dll from debug/pe. More details in CryptoAlg-907.

### Testing:
This change was tested in isolation and as a part of https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/433 with a complete end to end flow for the WIndows FIPS build.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Addresses `CryptoAlg-895` 

### Description of changes: 
AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/pull/617/files), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains, mitigating past issues like this: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

### Call-outs:
`ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` in `tests/ci/android/AWSLCAndroidTestRunner/app/src/main/cpp/CMakeLists.txt` is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC that compiles our test executables from regular executables to `so` executables when `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` is on. Only Shared Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs need to be outputted as an `so` for `AWSLCAndroidTestRunner`  to be able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` change in AWS-LC is not in this PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.
 
### Testing:
How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?
Test with proof of concept in a PR on my fork: https://github.com/samuel40791765/aws-lc/pull/6

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

When we added the [integration test for AWS-LC FIPS](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/commit/6040c6afd8733c19c1b9ca7fa448629fc4b5dac3) on 2021-11-05 we had not cut the official branch yet so the test used AWS-LC's main. AWS-LC now has a [branch](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/tree/fips-2021-10-20) ready for use (it was finalized on 2021-12-22). The unfortunate part is [this s2n change (2022-02-01)](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/commit/b956eab5f1676a961b16cb060d41c3844e118af2) changed this memory usage from 49 to 48 which works with the FIPS build of AWS-LC main, but not the FIPS branch. The FIPS branch is based on AWS-LC code from 2021-12-22 and does not have the recent memory savings that this test is relying on.

### Call-outs:
I am hunting down the specific AWS-LC change(s) on main that is saving the memory this test expects. The good news is this can be changed back to a 48 after the next FIPS validation that takes all the latest changes from main.

### Testing:
Tested locally running the install script and unit tests.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

The assembly source is from this OpenSSL's commit: 
https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/9ce8e0d17e608de4f85f7543c52b146e3c6a2291:
* Some comments were added to the Perl Assembly implementation on `{prefix}_xts_encrypt`.
* BTI instructions were added at the beginning of `{prefix}_xts_encrypt` and `{prefix}_xts_decrypt`.
* Test vectors were added in order to test the different paths of the AArch64 implementation.
* Checks that the 2 keys are different and that the input size does not exceed 2^{20} are also added to the functions `aes_xts_init_key` and `aes_xts_cipher`, respectively.

Call-outs:
* `libdecrepit` was added as a dependency of the `bssl` tool in order to run the speed test.

P-384 and P-521 scalar multiplication with smaller tables 

This commit changes the size of the precomputed tables used in scalar
multiplication fuctions of P-384 and P-521 implementations.
Our experiments show that we can have approximately the same performance
with much smaller tables. Previously, we were using tables of size:
  - 86KB and 175KB for the precomputed table of base point multiples
    in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively. This table is used in
    mul_base and mul_public functions.
  - 9KB and 14KB for the table computed on-the-fly in mul function
    in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively.
Note that the tables in the first case are precomputed and are part
of the binary (libcrypto.so), while the tables in the second case
are computed in runtime and don't affect the binary size.

With this commit we change the tables and obtain the following savings:
  - the precomputed table: from 86KB to 30KB and from 175KB to 62KB,
  - the on-the-fly table: from 9KB to 2KB and from 14KB to 4KB,
in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively. The performance comparison
between the new and the old tables is shown in the tables below
(the performance is measure in number of operations per second by the
bssl speed tool).

Intel(R) Xeon(R) Platinum 8124M CPU (x86_64)
  | Operation           |  Old (86KB+9KB)   |  New (30KB+2KB)   |
  | P-384 ECDH          |       3747        |       4092        |
  | P-384 ECDSA sign    |      10651        |      10510        |
  | P-384 ECDSA verify  |       4457        |       4324        |
   -------------------------------------------------------------
  |                     | Old (175KB+14KB)  |  New (62KB+4KB)   |
  | P-521 ECDH          |       2857        |       3088        |
  | P-521 ECDSA sign    |       5673        |       5679        |
  | P-521 ECDSA verify  |       2782        |       2698        |

Graviton 2 (ARMv8, aarch64)
  | Operation           |  Old (86KB+9KB)   |  New (30KB+2KB)   |
  | P-384 ECDH          |       1787        |       2009        |
  | P-384 ECDSA sign    |       4447        |       4480        |
  | P-384 ECDSA verify  |       2085        |       2085        |
   -------------------------------------------------------------

(#442)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/8fee0a8e090f7d8c493bb64481503bdf5f53a428'}, {'sha': '14decef741ec1e1f5e24f1d4a4f8d2378a12e94f', 'author': {'email': 'SalusaSecondus@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Greg Rubin'}, 'message': 'Optimized HMAC implementions (#368)

Profiling the existing EVP-based HMAC implementations shows that much of their time is spent in memory management functions and EVP overhead. (In some cases it is more that 5%.) Additionally the EVP APIs do heap-based memory allocation internally.

The more involvement memory management can cause problems for some consumers, specifically those with their own memory management concerns:

* Applications using custom allocators (including zero-allocation)
* Applications with tight time constraints (as malloc/free and be expensive)
* Foreign Function Interface (FFI) applications such as Java
* Allocating/Freeing/Copying items on the heap require expensive FFI calls
* Stack-based items can commonly be stored in memory managed by the caller (such as Java) and so be allocated/freed/copy without FFI calls.

By refactoring the HMAC code so that all state lives locally in a single stack-allocatable object we can significantly improve performance.', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/14decef741ec1e1f5e24f1d4a4f8d2378a12e94f'}, {'sha': '077ec414034b75b53a3f8c5a43ebb5832bca6d5e', 'author': {'email': 'andhop@amazon.com', 'name': 'Andrew Hopkins'}, 'message': 'Update the analytics to only run on the main branch (#444)

(#442)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/8fee0a8e090f7d8c493bb64481503bdf5f53a428'}, {'sha': '14decef741ec1e1f5e24f1d4a4f8d2378a12e94f', 'author': {'email': 'SalusaSecondus@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Greg Rubin'}, 'message': 'Optimized HMAC implementions (#368)

Profiling the existing EVP-based HMAC implementations shows that much of their time is spent in memory management functions and EVP overhead. (In some cases it is more that 5%.) Additionally the EVP APIs do heap-based memory allocation internally.

The more involvement memory management can cause problems for some consumers, specifically those with their own memory management concerns:

* Applications using custom allocators (including zero-allocation)
* Applications with tight time constraints (as malloc/free and be expensive)
* Foreign Function Interface (FFI) applications such as Java
* Allocating/Freeing/Copying items on the heap require expensive FFI calls
* Stack-based items can commonly be stored in memory managed by the caller (such as Java) and so be allocated/freed/copy without FFI calls.

By refactoring the HMAC code so that all state lives locally in a single stack-allocatable object we can significantly improve performance.', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/14decef741ec1e1f5e24f1d4a4f8d2378a12e94f'}]}

+# Android CI for AWS-LC
+AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/tree/main/AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. This app can be tested with the docker image at `tests/ci/docker_images/linux-x86/ubuntu-20.04_android`.
+
+## Setup
+1. Assuming all the commands are being run from this folder: `cd tests/ci/android`
+2. `docker build -t ubuntu-20.04:android ../docker_images/linux-x86/ubuntu-20.04_android/`
+3. Run the docker image from root of aws-lc. The container needs access to aws-lc's source code to build.
+   ```

False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Addresses `CryptoAlg-895` 

### Description of changes: 
AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/pull/617/files), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains, mitigating past issues like this: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

### Call-outs:
`ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` in `tests/ci/android/AWSLCAndroidTestRunner/app/src/main/cpp/CMakeLists.txt` is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC that compiles our test executables from regular executables to `so` executables when `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` is on. Only Shared Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs need to be outputted as an `so` for `AWSLCAndroidTestRunner`  to be able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` change in AWS-LC is not in this PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.
 
### Testing:
How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?
Test with proof of concept in a PR on my fork: https://github.com/samuel40791765/aws-lc/pull/6

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

+# Android CI for AWS-LC
+AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/tree/main/AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. This app can be tested with the docker image at `tests/ci/docker_images/linux-x86/ubuntu-20.04_android`.
+
+## Setup

False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Addresses `CryptoAlg-895` 

### Description of changes: 
AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/pull/617/files), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains, mitigating past issues like this: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

### Call-outs:
`ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` in `tests/ci/android/AWSLCAndroidTestRunner/app/src/main/cpp/CMakeLists.txt` is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC that compiles our test executables from regular executables to `so` executables when `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` is on. Only Shared Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs need to be outputted as an `so` for `AWSLCAndroidTestRunner`  to be able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` change in AWS-LC is not in this PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.
 
### Testing:
How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?
Test with proof of concept in a PR on my fork: https://github.com/samuel40791765/aws-lc/pull/6

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Addresses `CryptoAlg-895` 

### Description of changes: 
AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/pull/617/files), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains, mitigating past issues like this: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

### Call-outs:
`ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` in `tests/ci/android/AWSLCAndroidTestRunner/app/src/main/cpp/CMakeLists.txt` is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC that compiles our test executables from regular executables to `so` executables when `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` is on. Only Shared Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs need to be outputted as an `so` for `AWSLCAndroidTestRunner`  to be able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` change in AWS-LC is not in this PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.
 
### Testing:
How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?
Test with proof of concept in a PR on my fork: https://github.com/samuel40791765/aws-lc/pull/6

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

+# Android CI for AWS-LC
+AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/tree/main/AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. This app can be tested with the docker image at `tests/ci/docker_images/linux-x86/ubuntu-20.04_android`.
+
+## Setup
+1. Assuming all the commands are being run from this folder: `cd tests/ci/android`
+2. `docker build -t ubuntu-20.04:android ../docker_images/linux-x86/ubuntu-20.04_android/`
+3. Run the docker image from root of aws-lc. The container needs access to aws-lc's source code to build.
+   ```

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/samuel40791765/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Addresses `CryptoAlg-895` 

### Description of changes: 
AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/pull/617/files), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains, mitigating past issues like this: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

### Call-outs:
`ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` in `tests/ci/android/AWSLCAndroidTestRunner/app/src/main/cpp/CMakeLists.txt` is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC that compiles our test executables from regular executables to `so` executables when `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` is on. Only Shared Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs need to be outputted as an `so` for `AWSLCAndroidTestRunner`  to be able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` change in AWS-LC is not in this PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.
 
### Testing:
How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?
Test with proof of concept in a PR on my fork: https://github.com/samuel40791765/aws-lc/pull/6

False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Addresses `CryptoAlg-895` 

### Description of changes: 
AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/pull/617/files), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains, mitigating past issues like this: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

### Call-outs:
`ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` in `tests/ci/android/AWSLCAndroidTestRunner/app/src/main/cpp/CMakeLists.txt` is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC that compiles our test executables from regular executables to `so` executables when `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` is on. Only Shared Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs need to be outputted as an `so` for `AWSLCAndroidTestRunner`  to be able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` change in AWS-LC is not in this PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.
 
### Testing:
How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?
Test with proof of concept in a PR on my fork: https://github.com/samuel40791765/aws-lc/pull/6

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

False}, 'body': "### Issues:
Addresses `CryptoAlg-895` 

### Description of changes: 
AWS-LC wants to ensure that our tests and build work correctly on Android. Insipred from the CRT Team's [`AWSCRTAndroidTestRunner`](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-c-common/pull/617/files), this mini Android test harness is intended to be used within our Android CI with AWS Device Farm. The tests will include `crypto_test`, `urandom_test`, `decrepit_test` and `ssl_test`, referenced from regular test dimensions. 
Using this test harness with AWS-LC will also help ensure that builds cross compiles successfully with the Android toolchains, mitigating past issues like this: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/192.

### Call-outs:
`ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` in `tests/ci/android/AWSLCAndroidTestRunner/app/src/main/cpp/CMakeLists.txt` is a new flag that I plan to add in AWS-LC that compiles our test executables from regular executables to `so` executables when `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` is on. Only Shared Object files can be automatically packaged into an Android app with the right execution permissions, so test executable outputs need to be outputted as an `so` for `AWSLCAndroidTestRunner`  to be able to execute the tests within the app dimension.
The actual `ANDROIDTESTRUNNER` change in AWS-LC is not in this PR, and this is just an early call out to the change I intend to make.
 
### Testing:
How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?
Test with proof of concept in a PR on my fork: https://github.com/samuel40791765/aws-lc/pull/6

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

{'push_id': 9452002184, 'size': 8, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/main', 'head': '18609aab18081d7ee5452f8eee4db54b122312c9', 'before': '67a873752690af8446d75b1ef564261ac57a0668', 'commits': [{'sha': 'f4f85c7310f61300539c688ed315e9b207151766', 'author': {'email': '66388554+nebeid@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Nevine Ebeid'}, 'message': "Integration of AES-XTS AArch64 implementation (#400)

The assembly source is from this OpenSSL's commit: 
https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/9ce8e0d17e608de4f85f7543c52b146e3c6a2291:
* Some comments were added to the Perl Assembly implementation on `{prefix}_xts_encrypt`.
* BTI instructions were added at the beginning of `{prefix}_xts_encrypt` and `{prefix}_xts_decrypt`.
* Test vectors were added in order to test the different paths of the AArch64 implementation.
* Checks that the 2 keys are different and that the input size does not exceed 2^{20} are also added to the functions `aes_xts_init_key` and `aes_xts_cipher`, respectively.

Call-outs:
* `libdecrepit` was added as a dependency of the `bssl` tool in order to run the speed test.

Performance improvement:
Init and Encrypt:
|      Size   | Before (MB/s)(1) | After (MB/s) | Improvement |
-------------:|-----------------:|-------------:|:------------:
|    16 bytes |        88        |       91     |    1.03x    |
|   256 bytes |       647        |      883     |    1.36x    |
|  1350 bytes |       971        |     1804     |    1.86x    |
|  8192 bytes |      1097        |     2334     |    2.13x    |
| 16384 bytes |      1109        |     2398     |    2.16x    |

Init and Decrypt:
|      Size   | Before (MB/s)(1) | After (MB/s) | Improvement |
-------------:|-----------------:|-------------:|:------------:
|    16 bytes |        83        |       85     |    1.02x    |
|   256 bytes |       621        |      810     |    1.30x    |

P-384 and P-521 scalar multiplication with smaller tables 

This commit changes the size of the precomputed tables used in scalar
multiplication fuctions of P-384 and P-521 implementations.
Our experiments show that we can have approximately the same performance
with much smaller tables. Previously, we were using tables of size:
  - 86KB and 175KB for the precomputed table of base point multiples
    in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively. This table is used in
    mul_base and mul_public functions.
  - 9KB and 14KB for the table computed on-the-fly in mul function
    in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively.
Note that the tables in the first case are precomputed and are part
of the binary (libcrypto.so), while the tables in the second case
are computed in runtime and don't affect the binary size.

With this commit we change the tables and obtain the following savings:
  - the precomputed table: from 86KB to 30KB and from 175KB to 62KB,
  - the on-the-fly table: from 9KB to 2KB and from 14KB to 4KB,
in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively. The performance comparison
between the new and the old tables is shown in the tables below
(the performance is measure in number of operations per second by the
bssl speed tool).

Intel(R) Xeon(R) Platinum 8124M CPU (x86_64)
  | Operation           |  Old (86KB+9KB)   |  New (30KB+2KB)   |
  | P-384 ECDH          |       3747        |       4092        |
  | P-384 ECDSA sign    |      10651        |      10510        |
  | P-384 ECDSA verify  |       4457        |       4324        |
   -------------------------------------------------------------
  |                     | Old (175KB+14KB)  |  New (62KB+4KB)   |
  | P-521 ECDH          |       2857        |       3088        |
  | P-521 ECDSA sign    |       5673        |       5679        |
  | P-521 ECDSA verify  |       2782        |       2698        |

Graviton 2 (ARMv8, aarch64)
  | Operation           |  Old (86KB+9KB)   |  New (30KB+2KB)   |
  | P-384 ECDH          |       1787        |       2009        |
  | P-384 ECDSA sign    |       4447        |       4480        |
  | P-384 ECDSA verify  |       2085        |       2085        |
   -------------------------------------------------------------
  |                     | Old (175KB+14KB)  |  New (62KB+4KB)   |
  | P-521 ECDH          |        799        |        877        |
  | P-521 ECDSA sign    |       1748        |       1744        |

From local testing there is a small difference between Clang and GCC.

This change also updates the webhook to pull the full history so it can get the timestamp from the commit. I missed this in local testing because triggering a CodeBuild build manually is different than the webhook which was missing all history and time. [CDK Clone Depth](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cdk/api/v1/docs/@aws-cdk_aws-codebuild.GitHubSourceProps.html#clonedepth)

### Testing:
Ran locally and verified sizes were still correct.

'body': "The benchmarking framework was complex and that led to difficulty
debugging issues, and eventually led to the discontinuation of it's
usage. This change simplifies the framework to provide easier debugging
as well as fixing some issues

### Description of changes: 
This updates the benchmarking framework in code to run directly on codebuild, stop looking for regressions compared to OpenSSL/BoringSSL and use a more accurate method for determining performance degradations.

### Call-outs:
This also enables the ci, but will not make it required on pull requests, so we can evaluate whether or not it fails too frequently before we start requiring it

### Testing:
This was manually tested in my developer account. I never saw a difference of above 5% from random chance with my changes so I think it's unlikely to cause spurious failures.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

'body': "The benchmarking framework was complex and that led to difficulty
debugging issues, and eventually led to the discontinuation of it's
usage. This change simplifies the framework to provide easier debugging
as well as fixing some issues

### Description of changes: 
This updates the benchmarking framework in code to run directly on codebuild, stop looking for regressions compared to OpenSSL/BoringSSL and use a more accurate method for determining performance degradations.

### Call-outs:
This also enables the ci, but will not make it required on pull requests, so we can evaluate whether or not it fails too frequently before we start requiring it

### Testing:
This was manually tested in my developer account. I never saw a difference of above 5% from random chance with my changes so I think it's unlikely to cause spurious failures.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

debugging issues, and eventually led to the discontinuation of it's
usage. This change simplifies the framework to provide easier debugging
as well as fixing some issues

### Description of changes: 
This updates the benchmarking framework in code to run directly on codebuild, stop looking for regressions compared to OpenSSL/BoringSSL and use a more accurate method for determining performance degradations.

### Call-outs:
This also enables the ci, but will not make it required on pull requests, so we can evaluate whether or not it fails too frequently before we start requiring it

### Testing:
This was manually tested in my developer account. I never saw a difference of above 5% from random chance with my changes so I think it's unlikely to cause spurious failures.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

'body': "The benchmarking framework was complex and that led to difficulty
debugging issues, and eventually led to the discontinuation of it's
usage. This change simplifies the framework to provide easier debugging
as well as fixing some issues

### Description of changes: 
This updates the benchmarking framework in code to run directly on codebuild, stop looking for regressions compared to OpenSSL/BoringSSL and use a more accurate method for determining performance degradations.

### Call-outs:
This also enables the ci, but will not make it required on pull requests, so we can evaluate whether or not it fails too frequently before we start requiring it

### Testing:
This was manually tested in my developer account. I never saw a difference of above 5% from random chance with my changes so I think it's unlikely to cause spurious failures.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-910

### Description of changes: 
This PR added test data for `|EVP_aes_128_cbc_hmac_sha1/256|`.
```sh
The *.txt files are generated by running below command.
# Working dir aws-lc/crypto/cipher_extra/test
./make_all_legacy_aead_tests.sh
```

### Call-outs:
* New PRs will import the code of `|EVP_aes_128_cbc_hmac_sha1/256|` from OpenSSL.

### Testing:
* The test data will be used when the code of `|EVP_aes_128_cbc_hmac_sha1/256|` from OpenSSL are imported.
* The test data were used in `stitch` branch of my personal repo.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

We're interested in several metrics about AWS-LC that might change over time. This change adds the start of a system that could track several of them in cloudwatch:
* Size of source code and top level folders
* For the combination of small, no asm, static/shared:
    * Build time for various dimensions
    * Test time for various dimensions
    * Size of libcrypto and libssl 
* FIPS is treated special since only one dimension is actually FIPS certified
* It's 9 builds in total and CodeBuild takes about 30 minutes to finish

### Call-outs:
I like the metric names because it is very clear what is happening and line up with CMake. One drawback is the names are a little long and make it clunky in the console. For example by default the label in the graph is just the **value** of the dimension, so things look like `ON ON OFF x86_64` and you have to line up. The dimension could be updated to `Assembly=NO_ASM` and `Assembly=ASM` so the console (by default) would look like `ASM SHARED non-FIPS x64_64`. Naming things is still hard and I'm interested in other opinions on the user experience.

### Testing:
I've deployed this to my account and browsed the metrics in CloudWatch looks reasonable. Happy to give people a tour in my account before deploying it to the team account.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

P-384 and P-521 scalar multiplication with smaller tables 

This commit changes the size of the precomputed tables used in scalar
multiplication fuctions of P-384 and P-521 implementations.
Our experiments show that we can have approximately the same performance
with much smaller tables. Previously, we were using tables of size:
  - 86KB and 175KB for the precomputed table of base point multiples
    in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively. This table is used in
    mul_base and mul_public functions.
  - 9KB and 14KB for the table computed on-the-fly in mul function
    in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively.
Note that the tables in the first case are precomputed and are part
of the binary (libcrypto.so), while the tables in the second case
are computed in runtime and don't affect the binary size.

With this commit we change the tables and obtain the following savings:
  - the precomputed table: from 86KB to 30KB and from 175KB to 62KB,
  - the on-the-fly table: from 9KB to 2KB and from 14KB to 4KB,
in P-384 and P-521 case, respectively. The performance comparison
between the new and the old tables is shown in the tables below
(the performance is measure in number of operations per second by the
bssl speed tool).

Intel(R) Xeon(R) Platinum 8124M CPU (x86_64)
  | Operation           |  Old (86KB+9KB)   |  New (30KB+2KB)   |
  | P-384 ECDH          |       3747        |       4092        |
  | P-384 ECDSA sign    |      10651        |      10510        |
  | P-384 ECDSA verify  |       4457        |       4324        |
   -------------------------------------------------------------
  |                     | Old (175KB+14KB)  |  New (62KB+4KB)   |
  | P-521 ECDH          |       2857        |       3088        |
  | P-521 ECDSA sign    |       5673        |       5679        |
  | P-521 ECDSA verify  |       2782        |       2698        |

Graviton 2 (ARMv8, aarch64)
  | Operation           |  Old (86KB+9KB)   |  New (30KB+2KB)   |
  | P-384 ECDH          |       1787        |       2009        |
  | P-384 ECDSA sign    |       4447        |       4480        |
  | P-384 ECDSA verify  |       2085        |       2085        |
   -------------------------------------------------------------
  |                     | Old (175KB+14KB)  |  New (62KB+4KB)   |
  | P-521 ECDH          |        799        |        877        |
  | P-521 ECDSA sign    |       1748        |       1744        |
  | P-521 ECDSA verify  |        827        |        810        |", 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/0fd46d134fbae9a2ad546e43f0e8581209dffa1c'}, {'sha': '1a7d85ebafd3ee96014258ed4613303340d403e8', 'author': {'email': 'andhop@amazon.com', 'name': 'Andrew Hopkins'}, 'message': "Merge branch 'main' into analytics", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/1a7d85ebafd3ee96014258ed4613303340d403e8'}]}

{'action': 'opened', 'number': 434, 'pull_request': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/awslabs/aws-lc/pulls/434', 'id': 886615780, 'node_id': 'PR_kwDOD7vRvs402K7k', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434', 'diff_url': 'https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434.diff', 'patch_url': 'https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/pull/434.patch', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/awslabs/aws-lc/issues/434', 'number': 434, 'state': 'open', 'locked': False, 'title': 'Separate the CMake logic to build libcrypto into a function', 'user': {'login': 'andrewhop', 'id': 41167468, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjQxMTY3NDY4', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/41167468?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/andrewhop', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change makes the logic to build libcrypto a separate function that takes a list of objects and static libraries to build it from. This change maintains the current behavior and only builds one libcrypto. The proposed design in CryptoAlg-907 and implemented in PR TBD uses this logic to build a lib_precrypto that generates the correct integrity fingerprint in a second fipsmodule to build the real libcrypto.

### Call-outs:
This is a draft while ironing out the design and implementation in TBD. I am currently going with this approach due to a potential limitation of  [debug/pe](https://pkg.go.dev/debug/pe) and/or the way we build libcrypto. The issue is getting the position of the symbols in crypto.dll from debug/pe. More details in CryptoAlg-907.

### Testing:

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change builds on the TBD change. It adds more FIPS MSVC specific fixes to our code and special build logic to handle the differences for MSVC and Windows in general. Specifically the new Windows build logic at a high level is:
1. Build all C files into object files using a CMake object library
2. Build the first fipmodule that contains the placeholder integrity hash
3. Build libprecrypto using the object files and fipsmodule
4. Build fips_empty_main linked with libprecrypto
5. Run capture_hash.go with fips_empty_main to generate generated_fips_shared_support.c with the correct hash
6. Build the final libcrypto with the original object files and generated_fips_shared_support

### Call-outs:
This only changes the FIPS Windows build, all other flavors and platforms should be unchanged. The Windows FIPS build currently only supports the Release No Assembly build flavor.

### Testing:
This change updates the Windows CI with a new FIPS build, and this was tested locally.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

(#416)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/eeffae102ae40fbde413532c2948128fc422099b'}, {'sha': '9ad27ab683afa084b096ee522161dc1ec24432f6', 'author': {'email': 'willck93@gmail.com', 'name': 'Will Childs-Klein'}, 'message': "Add new verification error for mismatched signatures (#413)

Overview
========
OpenSSL and AWS-LC differ in that OpenSSL [**does not** set][1] an error
code when it fails to verify an otherwise valid† ECDSA signature while
[BoringSSL][4] and [AWS-LC][2] **do**. AWS-LC sets the
error code `BAD_SIGNATURE` in this case, but also in the case of
malformed signatures. This conflation of concerns makes it impossible
for callers to distinguish between malfored and invalid signatures
(though there are reasonable arguments for why this conflation is
desirable).

This commit differentiates between the two cases by introducing a new
error code (`MISMATCHED_SIGNATURE`) and setting it in the case of
well-formed signatuer mismatch. We still set `BAD_SIGNATURE` for
malformed signatures. The new error codes' numerical values start at a
higher offset to allow for new upstream BoringSSL error codes to be
added.

AWS-LC's use of `BAD_SIGNATURE` error in _DSA_ verification feailure is
consistent with [AWS-LC's treatment of _RSA_ signature verification
failures][3], so this commit retains that consistency by applying the
same changes to both RSA and ECDSA.

AmazonCorrettoCryptoProvider (ACCP)
===================================
When we (ACCP) see an error after attempting (non-RSA) verification, we
[throw an exception][8]. Unfortunately, because AWS-LC currently
conflates _malformed_ and _inauthentic_ signatures under the same
`BAD_SIGNATURE` error code, we can not differentiate the cases, and thus
will never return `false` on ECDSA verification -- we'll either return
`true` if the signature is valid and authentic, else throw. The
[javadocs][9] for `Signature.verify` seem to indicate that we should
indeed return boolean `false` on verification failure. In order to do
this, we'll need to make changes to AWS-LC to either set no error code
upon verification failure or to set a distinct code which we can key off
of.

Code Generation
===============

Error entries were added using this command:

```
$ go run ./util/make_errors.go ecdsa rsa
```

Auto-generated error code files were updated by invoking this script from
the root of the project:

```
$ python3 ./util/generate_build_files.py
```

========

[2]: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/blob/main/crypto/fipsmodule/ecdsa/ecdsa.c#L194-L197
[3]: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/blob/main/crypto/fipsmodule/rsa/rsa.c#L620-L621
[4]: https://boringssl.googlesource.com/boringssl/+/refs/heads/master/crypto/fipsmodule/ecdsa/ecdsa.c#194
[5]: https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/commit/dcbf8a7dc6fb5064b979739e2ffc590de61c39a2#diff-7fe3b81789f62d5bbf2ff0d8a6a8db06393630449ff914f9127f788084b06e49R481-R484
[6]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/security/java-cryptography-architecture-jca-reference-guide.html

On x86_64 platforms s2n-bignum uses bmi2 and adx instruction sets
for some of the P-384 functions. These instructions are not supported
by every x86 CPU. Previously, we checked in runtime if bmi2 and adx
are supported and if not we fallback to Fiat's implementation. This
solution had a drawback that we had to always compile both
s2n-bignum and Fiat code.

s2n-bignum implemented "alternative" implementations of functions
that don't require any special instructions. In this commit we integrate
those changes and instead of falling-back to Fiat's code we fall back
to s2n-bignum alternative implementations. The change has two
benefits:
  - s2n-bignum and Fiat are decoupled so we compile only one.
  - Performance improvement on x86 CPUs that don't support bmi2
     and adx instructions is x2.11, x1.58, x2.03 for ECDH, ECDSA sign,
     ECDSA verify, respectively.

The benchmark for a CPU without bmi2 and adx support, with
bssl/speed -filter “P-384”, before and after:
ECDH: 1594 —> 3372 (ops/s)
ECDSA Sign: 6332 —> 10000 (ops/s)
ECDSA Verify: 1981 —> 4019 (ops/s)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/8b28ae4d5c86ec16a9f1fc8211aeec8c9dc1b41e'}, {'sha': 'e6997a4d5b74db969feaf7cc6ccdf6c35c838116', 'author': {'email': '78765052+jargh@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'jargh'}, 'message': 'Merge pull request #26 from jargh/main

(#416)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/eeffae102ae40fbde413532c2948128fc422099b'}, {'sha': '9ad27ab683afa084b096ee522161dc1ec24432f6', 'author': {'email': 'willck93@gmail.com', 'name': 'Will Childs-Klein'}, 'message': "Add new verification error for mismatched signatures (#413)

Overview
========
OpenSSL and AWS-LC differ in that OpenSSL [**does not** set][1] an error
code when it fails to verify an otherwise valid† ECDSA signature while
[BoringSSL][4] and [AWS-LC][2] **do**. AWS-LC sets the
error code `BAD_SIGNATURE` in this case, but also in the case of
malformed signatures. This conflation of concerns makes it impossible
for callers to distinguish between malfored and invalid signatures
(though there are reasonable arguments for why this conflation is
desirable).

This commit differentiates between the two cases by introducing a new
error code (`MISMATCHED_SIGNATURE`) and setting it in the case of
well-formed signatuer mismatch. We still set `BAD_SIGNATURE` for
malformed signatures. The new error codes' numerical values start at a
higher offset to allow for new upstream BoringSSL error codes to be
added.

AWS-LC's use of `BAD_SIGNATURE` error in _DSA_ verification feailure is
consistent with [AWS-LC's treatment of _RSA_ signature verification
failures][3], so this commit retains that consistency by applying the
same changes to both RSA and ECDSA.

AmazonCorrettoCryptoProvider (ACCP)
===================================
When we (ACCP) see an error after attempting (non-RSA) verification, we
[throw an exception][8]. Unfortunately, because AWS-LC currently
conflates _malformed_ and _inauthentic_ signatures under the same
`BAD_SIGNATURE` error code, we can not differentiate the cases, and thus
will never return `false` on ECDSA verification -- we'll either return
`true` if the signature is valid and authentic, else throw. The
[javadocs][9] for `Signature.verify` seem to indicate that we should
indeed return boolean `false` on verification failure. In order to do
this, we'll need to make changes to AWS-LC to either set no error code
upon verification failure or to set a distinct code which we can key off
of.

Code Generation
===============

Error entries were added using this command:

```
$ go run ./util/make_errors.go ecdsa rsa
```

Auto-generated error code files were updated by invoking this script from
the root of the project:

```
$ python3 ./util/generate_build_files.py
```

========

[2]: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/blob/main/crypto/fipsmodule/ecdsa/ecdsa.c#L194-L197
[3]: https://github.com/awslabs/aws-lc/blob/main/crypto/fipsmodule/rsa/rsa.c#L620-L621
[4]: https://boringssl.googlesource.com/boringssl/+/refs/heads/master/crypto/fipsmodule/ecdsa/ecdsa.c#194
[5]: https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/commit/dcbf8a7dc6fb5064b979739e2ffc590de61c39a2#diff-7fe3b81789f62d5bbf2ff0d8a6a8db06393630449ff914f9127f788084b06e49R481-R484
[6]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/security/java-cryptography-architecture-jca-reference-guide.html
[7]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/security/SignatureException.html

[9]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/security/Signature.html#verify(byte[])

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "### Description of changes: 
We're interested in several metrics about AWS-LC that might change over time. This change adds the start of a system that could track several of them in cloudwatch:
* Size of source code and top level folders
* For the combination of small, no asm, static/shared:
    * Build time for various dimensions
    * Test time for various dimensions
    * Size of libcrypto and libssl 
* FIPS is treated special since only one dimension is actually FIPS certified
* It's 9 builds in total and CodeBuild takes about 30 minutes to finish

### Call-outs:
I like the metric names because it is very clear what is happening and line up with CMake. One drawback is the names are a little long and make it clunky in the console. For example by default the label in the graph is just the **value** of the dimension, so things look like `ON ON OFF x86_64` and you have to line up. The dimension could be updated to `Assembly=NO_ASM` and `Assembly=ASM` so the console (by default) would look like `ASM SHARED non-FIPS x64_64`. Naming things is still hard and I'm interested in other opinions on the user experience.

### Testing:
I've deployed this to my account and browsed the metrics in CloudWatch looks reasonable. Happy to give people a tour in my account before deploying it to the team account.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Description of changes: 
We're interested in several metrics about AWS-LC that might change over time. This change adds the start of a system that could track several of them in cloudwatch:
* Size of source code and top level folders
* For the combination of small, no asm, static/shared:
    * Build time for various dimensions
    * Test time for various dimensions
    * Size of libcrypto and libssl 
* FIPS is treated special since only one dimension is actually FIPS certified
* It's 9 builds in total and CodeBuild takes about 30 minutes to finish

### Call-outs:
I like the metric names because it is very clear what is happening and line up with CMake. One drawback is the names are a little long and make it clunky in the console. For example by default the label in the graph is just the **value** of the dimension, so things look like `ON ON OFF x86_64` and you have to line up. The dimension could be updated to `Assembly=NO_ASM` and `Assembly=ASM` so the console (by default) would look like `ASM SHARED non-FIPS x64_64`. Naming things is still hard and I'm interested in other opinions on the user experience.

### Testing:
I've deployed this to my account and browsed the metrics in CloudWatch looks reasonable. Happy to give people a tour in my account before deploying it to the team account.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

+#!/bin/bash
+set -exo pipefail
+# Copyright Amazon.com, Inc. or its affiliates. All Rights Reserved.
+# SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0
+
+source tests/ci/common_posix_setup.sh
+
+# The build and test time is not meant to be scientific benchmark, just to get a rough sense of changes overtime.
+# In case there is a weird change over time this recorded additional information about the host to the logs.
+lscpu
+
+branch=$(echo "$CODEBUILD_WEBHOOK_TRIGGER" | cut -d '/' -f2)
+common_dimensions="Branch=${branch}"
+
+function put_metric {
+  # This call to publish the metric could fail but we don't want to fail the build +e turns off exit on error
+  set +e
+  aws cloudwatch put-metric-data \
+    --namespace AWS-LC \
+    "$@" || echo "Publishing metric failed, continuing with the rest of the build"
+  # Turn it back on for the rest of the build
+  set -e
+}
+
+# Return the size of an object or total for the folder (summarize)
+function size {
+  du --bytes --apparent-size --summarize "$@" | cut -f1
+}
+
+SOURCE_CODE_SIZE=$(size "$SRC_ROOT")
+put_metric --metric-name FolderSize --value "$SOURCE_CODE_SIZE" --unit Bytes --dimensions "Folder=root,${common_dimensions}"
+
+for FOLDER_PATH in "$SRC_ROOT"/*/ ; do
+    FOLDER_SIZE=$(size "$FOLDER_PATH")
+    FOLDER=$(basename "$FOLDER_PATH")
+    put_metric --metric-name FolderSize --value "$FOLDER_SIZE" --unit Bytes --dimensions "Folder=${FOLDER},${common_dimensions}"
+done
+

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "### Description of changes: 
We're interested in several metrics about AWS-LC that might change over time. This change adds the start of a system that could track several of them in cloudwatch:
* Size of source code and top level folders
* For the combination of small, no asm, static/shared:
    * Build time for various dimensions
    * Test time for various dimensions
    * Size of libcrypto and libssl 
* FIPS is treated special since only one dimension is actually FIPS certified
* It's 9 builds in total and CodeBuild takes about 30 minutes to finish

### Call-outs:
I like the metric names because it is very clear what is happening and line up with CMake. One drawback is the names are a little long and make it clunky in the console. For example by default the label in the graph is just the **value** of the dimension, so things look like `ON ON OFF x86_64` and you have to line up. The dimension could be updated to `Assembly=NO_ASM` and `Assembly=ASM` so the console (by default) would look like `ASM SHARED non-FIPS x64_64`. Naming things is still hard and I'm interested in other opinions on the user experience.

### Testing:
I've deployed this to my account and browsed the metrics in CloudWatch looks reasonable. Happy to give people a tour in my account before deploying it to the team account.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Description of changes: 
We're interested in several metrics about AWS-LC that might change over time. This change adds the start of a system that could track several of them in cloudwatch:
* Size of source code and top level folders
* For the combination of small, no asm, static/shared:
    * Build time for various dimensions
    * Test time for various dimensions
    * Size of libcrypto and libssl 
* FIPS is treated special since only one dimension is actually FIPS certified
* It's 9 builds in total and CodeBuild takes about 30 minutes to finish

### Call-outs:
I like the metric names because it is very clear what is happening and line up with CMake. One drawback is the names are a little long and make it clunky in the console. For example by default the label in the graph is just the **value** of the dimension, so things look like `ON ON OFF x86_64` and you have to line up. The dimension could be updated to `Assembly=NO_ASM` and `Assembly=ASM` so the console (by default) would look like `ASM SHARED non-FIPS x64_64`. Naming things is still hard and I'm interested in other opinions on the user experience.

### Testing:
I've deployed this to my account and browsed the metrics in CloudWatch looks reasonable. Happy to give people a tour in my account before deploying it to the team account.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This pulls in the latest changes from upstream Jitter. Highlights include:
* Multiple [MSVC fixes](https://github.com/smuellerDD/jitterentropy-library/commit/8373b05f1a55878f348d365f05b046ff42d2f9ce), [2](https://github.com/smuellerDD/jitterentropy-library/commit/f288b6aacf9927b059ba267ef16779e2fb13b507), and [3](https://github.com/smuellerDD/jitterentropy-library/commit/c68bd11c4c610a318f9ef4bd3011f8b04616396a)
* [Simplify and speed up backtrack protections](https://github.com/smuellerDD/jitterentropy-library/commit/52d974132eae7f541581bb133a1ce2c5dd9d8a4a)
* [All other commits](https://github.com/smuellerDD/jitterentropy-library/commits/master)

### Testing:
Other parts of the MSVC AWS-LC build is broken and can't be used to test the Jitter code on Windows yet. This was tested building Jitter by itself on a windows machine. The majority of the code is tested in our CI on Linux.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

* Address the comments.', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/d9af81604df30cf2b27539696736ddbfdaedf754'}, {'sha': '27c9918d99435db9588a475d1e0dac561b1fe838', 'author': {'email': 'andhop@amazon.com', 'name': 'Andrew Hopkins'}, 'message': 'Improve service indicator initialization and add tests for under/overflow (#422)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/27c9918d99435db9588a475d1e0dac561b1fe838'}, {'sha': '5159ff5579408150f95eee98bede23a0d8ca4e36', 'author': {'email': '25055813+dkostic@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'dkostic'}, 'message': 'P-521 implementation with s2n-bignum field arithmetic (#412)

This commit adds the implementation of P-521 curve that uses s2n-bignum
field arithmetic. The s2n-bignum library offers assembly implementation
optimized for x86_64 and aarch64 architectures. The integration is done
in the same way as for P-384. Basically, s2n-bignum field arithmetic
functions are designed as a drop-in replacement for their Fiat-crypto
counterparts. The one big difference between Fiat and s2n-bignum in
this case is that they use a different representation of field elements.
Because of this we need to generate different table of pre-computed
multiples of the base point for s2n-bignum. The rest of the integration
is a straightforward replacement of Fiat with s2n-bignum functions.

Finally, the performance improvements of this change are:

Intel(R) Xeon(R) Platinum 8124M CPU (x86_64)
| Operation           | Before(ops/sec) | After(ops/sec) | Improvement |
| ECDH P-521          |       1610      |      2865      |     1.8x    |
| ECDSA P-521 signing |       4300      |      5693      |     1.3x    |
| ECDSA P-521 verify  |       1767      |      2781      |     1.6x    |

Graviton 2 (ARMv8, aarch64)
| Operation           | Before(ops/sec) | After(ops/sec) | Improvement |
| ECDH P-521          |        532      |       802      |     1.5x    |
| ECDSA P-521 signing |       1460      |      1748      |     1.2x    |
| ECDSA P-521 verify  |        575      |       825      |     1.4x    |', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/5159ff5579408150f95eee98bede23a0d8ca4e36'}, {'sha': '11b50d39cf2378703a4ca6b6fee9d76a2e9852d1', 'author': {'email': '25055813+dkostic@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'dkostic'}, 'message': 'OpenSSL CVE-2022-0778 Fix possible infinite loop in BN_mod_sqrt() (#423)

OpenSSL CVE-2022-0778 Fix possible infinite loop in BN_mod_sqrt()

This commit fixes the issue released as OpenSSL CVE-2022-0778 that
affects AWS-LC as well. A bug in BN_mod_sqrt() can cause the function
to enter an infinite loop. The issue is now fixed and two test
cases are added to verify that the function returns a failure instead
of hanging.

We're interested in several metrics about AWS-LC that might change over time. This change adds the start of a system that could track several of them in cloudwatch:
* Size of source code and top level folders
* For the combination of small, no asm, static/shared:
    * Build time for various dimensions
    * Test time for various dimensions
    * Size of libcrypto and libssl 
* FIPS is treated special since only one dimension is actually FIPS certified
* It's 9 builds in total and CodeBuild takes about 30 minutes to finish

### Call-outs:
I like the metric names because it is very clear what is happening and line up with CMake. One drawback is the names are a little long and make it clunky in the console. For example by default the label in the graph is just the **value** of the dimension, so things look like `ON ON OFF x86_64` and you have to line up. The dimension could be updated to `Assembly=NO_ASM` and `Assembly=ASM` so the console (by default) would look like `ASM SHARED non-FIPS x64_64`. Naming things is still hard and I'm interested in other opinions on the user experience.

### Testing:
I've deployed this to my account and browsed the metrics in CloudWatch looks reasonable. Happy to give people a tour in my account before deploying it to the team account.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change replaces all Linux specific headers and APIs with a portable C++ standard library implementation instead of maintaining two platform specific implementations. Summary of issues/changes:
* unistd.h is a POSIX operating system header which is not available on Windows
     *  This provides `STDOUT_FILENO`
* sys/uio.h defines Linux vectorized IO operations
     *  This provides `iovec` which is used by `writev`

### Call-outs:
There could be performance implications switching from vectorizied IO to the buffered streams. The module wrapper is not performance critical and just needs to facilitate testing in a reasonable amount of time. In unscientific experiments locally this change takes the same time as before to run the acvp_tests.

Full Windows support will be added in a follow up PR. This change is needed for Windows support and this does build on Windows. The outstanding test failure will most likely be fixed in acvp.go or check_expected.go.

### Testing:
The run_tests target in our CI runs the acvp_tests which runs the modulewrapper with the existing tests. Timing the execution time with `time` on a Linux machine shows no performance regressions.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/andrewhop/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### Issues:
Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
This change replaces all Linux specific headers and APIs with a portable C++ standard library implementation instead of maintaining two platform specific implementations. Summary of issues/changes:
* unistd.h is a POSIX operating system header which is not available on Windows
     *  This provides `STDOUT_FILENO`
* sys/uio.h defines Linux vectorized IO operations
     *  This provides `iovec` which is used by `writev`

### Call-outs:
There could be performance implications switching from vectorizied IO to the buffered streams. The module wrapper is not performance critical and just needs to facilitate testing in a reasonable amount of time. In unscientific experiments locally this change takes the same time as before to run the acvp_tests.

Full Windows support will be added in a follow up PR. This change is needed for Windows support and this does build on Windows. The outstanding test failure will most likely be fixed in acvp.go or check_expected.go.

### Testing:
The run_tests target in our CI runs the acvp_tests which runs the modulewrapper with the existing tests. Timing the execution time with `time` on a Linux machine shows no performance regressions.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

{'push_id': 9359773679, 'size': 4, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/windows_acvp', 'head': '05dd8bef4708fba8b4f90f106233c29921d903c8', 'before': '3d77d61ee3d4412c68cf3730aac5203cbee9d823', 'commits': [{'sha': '27c9918d99435db9588a475d1e0dac561b1fe838', 'author': {'email': 'andhop@amazon.com', 'name': 'Andrew Hopkins'}, 'message': 'Improve service indicator initialization and add tests for under/overflow (#422)', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/27c9918d99435db9588a475d1e0dac561b1fe838'}, {'sha': '5159ff5579408150f95eee98bede23a0d8ca4e36', 'author': {'email': '25055813+dkostic@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'dkostic'}, 'message': 'P-521 implementation with s2n-bignum field arithmetic (#412)

This commit adds the implementation of P-521 curve that uses s2n-bignum
field arithmetic. The s2n-bignum library offers assembly implementation
optimized for x86_64 and aarch64 architectures. The integration is done
in the same way as for P-384. Basically, s2n-bignum field arithmetic
functions are designed as a drop-in replacement for their Fiat-crypto
counterparts. The one big difference between Fiat and s2n-bignum in
this case is that they use a different representation of field elements.
Because of this we need to generate different table of pre-computed
multiples of the base point for s2n-bignum. The rest of the integration
is a straightforward replacement of Fiat with s2n-bignum functions.

Finally, the performance improvements of this change are:

Intel(R) Xeon(R) Platinum 8124M CPU (x86_64)
| Operation           | Before(ops/sec) | After(ops/sec) | Improvement |
| ECDH P-521          |       1610      |      2865      |     1.8x    |
| ECDSA P-521 signing |       4300      |      5693      |     1.3x    |
| ECDSA P-521 verify  |       1767      |      2781      |     1.6x    |

Graviton 2 (ARMv8, aarch64)
| Operation           | Before(ops/sec) | After(ops/sec) | Improvement |
| ECDH P-521          |        532      |       802      |     1.5x    |
| ECDSA P-521 signing |       1460      |      1748      |     1.2x    |
| ECDSA P-521 verify  |        575      |       825      |     1.4x    |', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/5159ff5579408150f95eee98bede23a0d8ca4e36'}, {'sha': '11b50d39cf2378703a4ca6b6fee9d76a2e9852d1', 'author': {'email': '25055813+dkostic@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'dkostic'}, 'message': 'OpenSSL CVE-2022-0778 Fix possible infinite loop in BN_mod_sqrt() (#423)

OpenSSL CVE-2022-0778 Fix possible infinite loop in BN_mod_sqrt()

This commit fixes the issue released as OpenSSL CVE-2022-0778 that
affects AWS-LC as well. A bug in BN_mod_sqrt() can cause the function
to enter an infinite loop. The issue is now fixed and two test
cases are added to verify that the function returns a failure instead
of hanging.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
THis change replaces all Linux specific headers and APIs with a portable C++ standard library implementation. Summary of issues/changes:
* unistd.h is a POSIX operating system header which is not available on Windows
     *  This provides `STDOUT_FILENO`
* sys/uio.h defines Linux vectorized IO operations
     *  This provides `iovec` which is used by `writev`

### Call-outs:
There could be performance implications switching from vectorizied IO to the buffered streams. The module wrapper is not performance critical and just needs to facilitate testing in a reasonable amount of time. In unscientific experiments locally this change takes the same time as before to run the acvp_tests.

Full Windows support will be added in a follow up PR. This change is needed for Windows support and this does build on Windows. The outstanding test failure will most likely be fixed in acvp.go or check_expected.go.

### Testing:
The run_tests target in our CI runs the acvp_tests which runs the modulewrapper with the existing tests. Timing the execution time with `time` on a Linux machine shows no performance regressions.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
Add lazy initialization logic to all service indicator functions. This is *not* an issue for the current Linux FIPS branch. This issue only happens on Windows FIPS builds. The Windows issue is nothing was calling `FIPS_service_indicator_update_state` which created the state before calling `FIPS_service_indicator_lock_state`. When lock was called with a null state nothing happens and AWS-LC continues and eventually hits a call to update state which creates the state, then something calls unlock and underflows. My hypothesis is MSVC changes the order of self tests in the `BORINGSSL_bcm_power_on_self_test` to hit this unlock issue while Clang/GCC does not.

### Call-outs:
The CI does not test FIPS on Windows yet due to other issues. I have tested this part on a Windows machine manually and it addressed the issue. On Linux there is no behavior change.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Addresses CryptoAlg-907

### Description of changes: 
Add lazy initialization logic to all service indicator functions. This is *not* an issue for the current Linux FIPS branch. This issue only happens on Windows FIPS builds. The Windows issue is nothing was calling `FIPS_service_indicator_update_state` which created the state before calling `FIPS_service_indicator_lock_state`. When lock was called with a null state nothing happens and AWS-LC continues and eventually hits a call to update state which creates the state, then something calls unlock and underflows. My hypothesis is MSVC changes the order of self tests in the `BORINGSSL_bcm_power_on_self_test` to hit this unlock issue while Clang/GCC does not.

### Call-outs:
The CI does not test FIPS on Windows yet due to other issues. I have tested this part on a Windows machine manually and it addressed the issue. On Linux there is no behavior change.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

Added a minimal spec for the `EC_KEY_check_fips` function so that this function can be called when deriving keys using ECDH. The functional spec is undefined, so I don't specify or verify what this function actually does. The spec for `EVP_PKEY_derive` assumes that the supplied public key passes this check. We would need to do additional work to verify the behavior of `EVP_PKEY_derive` on keys that do not pass this check. Actually verifying the correctness and memory safety of `EC_KEY_check_fips` would also require additional work.

While I was updating the README, I also found and corrected an error. The length of the derived key is 48 bytes, not 384. 

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

{'push_id': 9309860497, 'size': 344, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/jitter', 'head': '49b3b9de55ad90a9f49ab4e6229369873fc0f058', 'before': 'cdb00a3a92b6fbd76812254e27029dd8af47c6f9', 'commits': [{'sha': '8917b847938216a1b410b2482f69b67ba707ca2e', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Make all directory names lowercase

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/e135d896544a0d63b7bed74675216d7f36d76aa8', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/8917b847938216a1b410b2482f69b67ba707ca2e'}, {'sha': '6e366dc0377f3a51e9a526bc83dd8e2183a857f0', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add 256-bit and 384-bit big-endian conversions

The functions are called "bignum_bigendian_4" (4 words = 256 bits) and
"bignum_bigendian_6" (6 words = 384 bits), with additional aliases
using names "...frombytes..." and "...tobytes...", treating either
input or output as a byte array (exactly the same code, but with a
different type in the C prototype). Each such alias has its own
variant correctness theorem stated slightly differently.

Although they are not specific to the P-256 and P-384 primes (only
their native sizes) they are located in the respective "p256" and
"p384" subdirectories, since the main anticipated uses are in
connection with those primes.

For a little-endian platform, these always amount to byte reversal.
The ARM code has not been tested in a big-endian instantiation, and
since the current ARM model assumes little-endianness a priori,
neither has it been verified in a big-endian setting, but it is
supposed to work there. This is not relevant for x86, which is always
little-endian.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/99cd9044f288de42d3e317f04d9a13bf86754614', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/6e366dc0377f3a51e9a526bc83dd8e2183a857f0'}, {'sha': 'ffdbe549106255f0ea0ece83f1673ed3e6befe45', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add 256-bit and 384-bit specializations of multiplex/select

The functions are bignum_mux_4 and bignum_mux_6, and once again are
in the respective "p256" and "p384" subdirectories even though they

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/415d2561dcb388e1cf9f2bf040aa0adcfa020042', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/ffdbe549106255f0ea0ece83f1673ed3e6befe45'}, {'sha': '2c9862d786fa357ee8c277cbfaefb9a5a1680084', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add 256-bit and 384-bit specializations of nonzeroness test

The functions are bignum_nonzero_4 and bignum_nonzero_6, again in

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/355736c621d486117a0e585776d91816ff724ce1', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/2c9862d786fa357ee8c277cbfaefb9a5a1680084'}, {'sha': '53f5c4bcffc23f158f5a29432f21c31248f89d95', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Remove separate almost-Montgomery functions for P-256 and P-384

The almost-Montgomery multiplications and squarings, where full
modular reduction is not guaranteed, do not seem to offer enough
(or in many cases any) performance advantage at the small sizes
of P-256 and P-384, in contrast to larger RSA-sized operations.
These separate functions have been completely deleted, but the
proofs of the "full" Montgomery operations for the NIST primes
(bignum_montmul_p256 etc.) have been augmented with variants
showing that they also work as almost-Montgomery functions. That
is, even without assumptions on the input ranges beyond those
implicit in the native sizes, the appropriate congruence is
guaranteed. It would perhaps be more elegant to put both of these
statements in the same proof, since the current change involves
some duplication of the proof scripts.

This starts a new section "p521" devoted to special optimizations
related to the NIST P-521 curve, where the underlying field has
characteristic 2^521 - 1, a Mersenne prime. The function
bignum_add_p521 is modular addition w.r.t. this prime, by analogy with
the existing bignum_add_p256 and bignum_add_p384 functions.

The code previously had a mix of cases where the "#" prefix was
used before numeric literals and cases where it wasn't. It makes
no difference to gcc or the GNU assembler (and hence this change

things more consistent and may help other tools processing the

This makes sure each .S file has an explicit .text directive, and
also regularizes the positioning of these and the .globl ones (plus
the .intel_syntax ones for x86), collecting them at the beginning
just after the initial API comment banner. The only even slightly
non-trivial change is the removal of the global directive for
bignum_of_word_nontrivial in "x86/generic/bignum_of_word.S"
(this was not present for ARM, nor was it declared in the header).
There are no changes to code and hence no changes in the proofs.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/debfd4cbdd1db43c1df861dc185d07551b2503eb', 'distinct': False, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/andrewhop/aws-lc/commits/e8f61ab56f0b12c9153d47472b179c291294ff19'}, {'sha': '11f9fbb3008e3507561991f82a7226555bec99e2', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add non-executable stack directives to all asm files

This appends the following additional directive at the end of each
assembler file, so that the .o produced doesn't appear to need
executable stack:

  #if defined(__linux__) && defined(__ELF__)
  .section .note.GNU-stack,"",%progbits
  #endif

This follows the guidance here:

  https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki/Hardened/GNU_stack_quickstart#Patching
